<HEADLINE> Iraq Calls for Ending Turkish Military Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Iraq today called on Turkish forces
to immediately and unconditionally withdraw from Iraqi lands, a
day after Turkey announced that its operation was coming to an end.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq should stop exploiting the fragile situation in this part
of our country to satisfy their regional ambitions," said Nabil
Nejm, Iraq's permanent representative to the Cairo-based Arab
League.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with the League's Secretary General Esmat Abdel
Meguid here today, Nejm said that Turkish military operations in
northern Iraq had not ceased.
</P>
<P>
He was responding to an announcement by Turkish Prime Minister
Necmettin Erbakan Sunday that the Turkish army's 25-day-old
operation in northern Iraq had come to an end.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Turkish troops, backed by air power, poured into
northern Iraq on May 14 in a cross-border operation against
Kurdish Workers Party (PKK) bases used for raids into southeast
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The operation has attracted condemnation from the Arab League
secretariat and a demand that Turkish forces withdraw
immediately.
</P>
<P>
Nejm lauded the "positive and responsible stance" the Arab
League adopted toward the "Turkish invasion into Iraq."
</P>
<P>
"The Turkish incursion into Iraq is not the first and the Arab
nation refuses the Turkish justifications for it," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Arabs demand the immediate and unconditional withdrawal and
the maintaining of Turkish-Arab relations, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish military said they had killed 2,252 guerrillas in
the operation for the loss of 95 of their own troops. But the
rebels put losses by the army and its Iraqi Kurd alllies at almost
800 men. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
