<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan, Russia to Expand Economic Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Japan and Russia agreed today to
increase economic cooperation to promote Russia's economic reform
with Japan's investment and technical assistance, the Japanese
Foreign Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The accord was reached by Japanese Foreign Minister Yukihiko
Ikeda and Russia's first Deputy Prime Minister Boris Nemtsov when
they met for the second session of a bilateral governmental
committee on trade and economic issues.
</P>
<P>
During the session, they signed a 15-point memorandum calling
for mutual cooperation to speed up development of natural
resources in Russia's Far Eastern regions as well as to integrate
Russia into the international economic mechanism including the
World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
Japan has decided to provide about 100 million dollars of new
loans to Russia through the Export-Import Bank of Japan to finance
three projects in the Russian Far East.
</P>
<P>
The pact covering the loans, which will be part of the bank's
500 million dollar package pledged earlier, was signed today at
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Trade volume between Japan and Russia stood at about 5 billion
dollars in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
