<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Asks EU to Put off Budget Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 9 (Xinhua) -- France has requested on Monday a
"period of reflection" before the European Union countries adopt
budgetary rules in preparation for economic and monetary
union(EMU).
</P>
<P>
This request came at a meeting of EU finance ministers who held
talks in Luxembourg to discuss measures to ensure the stability of
the single currency euro, due to be introduced on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Within moments of the news, financial markets reportedly
reacted sharply with the French stock market and the franc falling
against the German mark.
</P>
<P>
New French Finance Minister Dominique Strauss-Kahn told his
counterparts at the meeting that Paris wanted time to consider the
"stability pact", agreed in Dublin in December, but not yet
ratified.
</P>
<P>
Paris would need at least a week, he said, adding that that
meant he did not believe it could be done by the EU's summit on
June 16-17 in Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
Strauss-Kahn said he did not want to renegotiate the pact.
Other EU ministers and officials were quick to say that the pact
could not be reopened.
</P>
<P>
"What has been agreed upon and discussed for two years can no
longer be put up for negotiation," German Finance Minister Theo
Waigal told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"No renegotiation of the stability pact is being demanded," he
said, but added that France wanted additional elements on
employment policy to be included in the so-called Maastricht II
treaty to be agreed at Amsterdam summit.
</P>
<P>
European Commission President Jacques Santer said he still
hoped for a deal by Amsterdam but that the new French government's
desire to discuss the issue was "understandable".
</P>
<P>
Dutch Finance Minister Gerrit Zalm, whose country currently
holds the EU rotating presidency, said he also hoped for a deal by
Amsterdam but acknowledged it could take time to integrate
France's demand for a greater coordination of economic policies.
</P>
<P>
The pact would place heavy fines on states within EU currency
union who ran excessive spending deficits after the euro is
introduced.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday night, the EU ministers approved in principle various
designs and technical specifications for euro coins. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
