<HEADLINE> UNEP Urges CITES to Reach Consensus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Environment
Program (UNEP) today urged the ongoing 10th conference of the
Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES)
to overcome differences and reach consensus.
</P>
<P>
"This conference has an opportunity to chart the critical path
leading to a conservation and sustainable use ethic," said UNEP
representative Elizabeth Dowdeswell at the opening of the CITES
conference.
</P>
<P>
He expected that an agreement could be signed during the
conference, under which UNEP would provide assistance to the
CITES secretariat.
</P>
<P>
Participants of the meeting are expected to look at more than
80 proposals and more than 60 resolutions.
</P>
<P>
There are 236 parties to the international organization, of
which 12 are new members. Three new members are expected to be
admitted the current meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
