<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BIS to 'Intensify' Relations with China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BASLE, SWITZERLAND, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The Bank for
Internationaln Settlements (BIS) is determined to further
intensify its relations with its new shareholder, the People's
Bank of China (PBC), BIS General Manager Andrew Crockett said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Answering questions at a press conference held at the BIS
headquarters, Crockett said that the PBC had actively participated
in many activities of the BIS committees and sub-committees at
different levels since PBC formally became a BIS member last
November. He appreciated the contributions which the PBC had made
to the BIS.
</P>
<P>
Crockett recalled his visit to Beijing a couple of weeks ago,
during which he "held consultations with senior Chinese officials
about further intensifications of relations" between the two banks.
</P>
<P>
He mentioned, in particular, PBC's participation in the
preparation of 21 core principles released by a BIS committee a
few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
The principles are now under consultation, hopefully to be
finalized at a BIS meeting scheduled in Hong Kong this September.
</P>
<P>
At the same press conference, the BIS Economic Adviser and Head
of the Monetary and Economic Department, William White, said that
sustainable development around the world, not just in China,
demands in the first instance a framework of macro-economic
stability, which means price stability and financial stability.
</P>
<P>
When asked how China would have sustainable development, White
said: "The biggest problem that China faces on the financial side
of the development is the restructuring of the state-owned
enterprises and government agencies, and state-owned banks that
lend money to them.
</P>
<P>
"This is a joint problem of the enterprises and the banks. I
have every confidence that the Chinese authorities are addressing
these challenging tasks in an appropriate way. I think they
recognize this is an important task at this juncture," White
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
