<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa, Libya Pledge to Promote Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 9 (Xinhua) -- South Africa and Libya today
signed in Pretoria an agreement to strenghten bilateral economic
and political cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"Our relations (with South Africa) on the politcial side have
been almost perfect. We hope to start seriously backing this up
with economic relations," Libyan Foreign Minister Omar Mustafa
Muntasser told reporters at the signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
South Africa needs Libya's petroleum products, while Libya
hopes to learn South African technological expertise in refining
petroleum, Muntasser said.
</P>
<P>
South African Foreign Minsiter Alfred Nzo said the latest
signed agreement demonstrated the determination of South Africa
and Libya to strengthen their all-round links.
</P>
<P>
During the ceremony, Muntasser reiterated Libyan leader
Muammar el-Gaddafy's intention of visiting South Africa. He said
the timing of such a trip would depend on when international
sanctions against Libya were lifted.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations imposed sanctions against Libya in 1992
because of its insistence on a neutral venue for the trial of two
Libyan citizens suspected to have been involved in the 1988
Lockerbie air disaster.
</P>
<P>
More than 250 people died when a Pan American aircraft
exploded over the town of Lockerbie in Scotland.
</P>
<P>
Britain, France and the United States have been demanding the
extradition of the suspects to Scotland to stand trial. The three
western states have rejected Libya's offer to deliver the two men
to the Hague International Court to be tried by Scottish judges
under Scottish law.
</P>
<P>
Munstasser reiterated his country's stance on the matter,
saying the two suspects were willing to subject themselves to a
trial in a neutral country.
</P>
<P>
Reaffirming South Africa's support for Libya's approach, Nzo
said, "Whenever this question arises...we suggest this should be
the way out for a solution of the problem." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Universal Principles Urged at CITES Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Decisions on the conservation of
wildlife resources should be based on universal principles, a
high-ranking official of the Convention on International Trade in
Endangered Species (CITES) Nobutoshi Akao said here today.
</P>
<P>
"Our decisions on these important issues must not be based on
emotion, but on credible scientific findings on the respect for
culture and traditions, and on the recognition of the different
values guiding the world," Akao told the opening session of the
parties to the conference.
</P>
<P>
"We must avoid double standards in our approach. It has become
all the more important for us to address challenges confronting
us in a new, innovative and creative way," he said.
</P>
<P>
Many proposals were made during the conference for new
listings, uplisting and downlisting of various species which
include the elephant, crocodile and white rhino.
</P>
<P>
He said the need for sustainable use of natural resources
advocated by the CITES was not a single-minded pursuit of one
specific philosophical approach to conservation, but should be
based on scientific data.
</P>
<P>
Because of this, Akao said, governments should be given full
responsibility to manage and protect their species.
</P>
<P>
"So long as this principle is maintained, there will be no
loss for anyone involved," he said, adding that it is extremely
important for the international community to changes the
traditional ways of addressing the issues.
</P>
<P>
About 1,300 delegates from around the world are attending the
ongoing conference convened to discuss the protection of
endangered species, while promoting other conservation
mechanisms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
