<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cook Rules out Early EMU Entry for Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 9 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook
has virtually ruled out the possibility of Britain joining the
European Monetary Union (EMU) in 1999 because the prospect of EMU
going ahead was increasingly unlikely.
</P>
<P>
Cook was quoted by press reports as saying on Sunday that the
recent events in Germany and France have made it less likely that
the single European currency would be implemented on January 1
1999.
</P>
<P>
He warned against easing any of the economic criteria for
joining the EMU and noted that the recent dispute between
Bundesbank and the German government on revaluing the country's
gold reserves have raised "significant questions" as to whether
the 1999 timetable could be reached.
</P>
<P>
On Britain's single currency membership, Cook said that it was
unlikely that Britain would want to join in the first wave and he
now considered it less than 50-50 that EMU would start before the
end of the century.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Secretary made it clear that Britain would carry
out a hard-headed assessment towards the end of this year as to
whether joining the single currency would be in the country's
economic interests.
</P>
<P>
"At the moment we think it's unlikely that that assessment
would point to us joining," he said, adding "If it proceeded on
time and it then proved a success, then in the long run Britain
could not stay outside."
</P>
<P>
He also signaled that Britain was closer to reaching an
agreement with its European Union partners over border controls by
saying "I am quite confident we are going to come away with a good
deal for Britain." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
