<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Considers UN-Demanded Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez
Boueiz stressed here today that the 1.7-million-dollar
compensation which a U.N. committee asks Israel to pay for its
shelling of a U.N. base last year "is less than what Lebanon has
demanded."
</P>
<P>
In a press conference held in his office this afternoon, the
foreign minister noted that Lebanon is sticking to its demands.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, the U.N. administrative and budgetary committee
adopted a resolution requiring Israel to pay more than 1.7
million U.S. dollars for damage resulting from its shelling of a
U.N. peacekeeping force camp at the south Lebanese town of Qana
on April 18, 1996.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 civilians taking refuge in the camp as well as
several Fijian soldiers of the U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon
(UNIFIL) were killed in the bombardment, making the day the
bloodiest of Israel's half-month-long "Grape of Wrath" operation
in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"The U.N. resolution is less than what Lebanon has demanded,
including clear (U.N.) condemnation, sanctions and compensations
of billions of dollars for the losses Israel caused for
Lebanon," the Lebanese foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
"We are sticking to the Lebanese complaints," Boueiz said,
adding that his government is waiting for a clarification from
Washington on a reported pressure U.S. officials exerted in order
to abort the bill.
</P>
<P>
Beirut media said this morning that the United States has
pressured Lebanon's U.N. delegation to "freeze" the resolution,
but the delegation has received instruction from its government
to press ahead with the bill to the finish.
</P>
<P>
The influential An-Nahar daily reported that U.S. officials
told the Lebanese side that if Lebanon did not freeze the draft
resolution, the U.S. team to the U.N. would block the automatic
renewal of the mandate of UNIFIL when it next comes up for
review at the U.N. Security Council in July.
</P>
<P>
Boueiz pointed out any pressure on Lebanon to force it to
withdraw the resolution "is at first a sabotage for the U.N.'s
role."
</P>
<P>
"We have to inquire what's the use of the U.N.'s existence if
it is not allowed to discuss and to hold a necessary session on
the most important massacre taking place since the end of the
Second World War," the Lebanese official underlined.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the U.S. pressure has caused an anger of
the Beirut media, and prompted the leftist daily As-Safir to say
that "the Americans do not tolerate any opposition to their
foreign policies especially when the Jewish State's welfare is
at stake."
</P>
<P>
Ash-Sharq daily said that "the Americans showed blind bias
when they threatened to sabotage Lebanon's bid to renew the
mandate of the UNIFIL forces in south Lebanon."
</P>
<P>
It said that this bias "goes against all international laws
and human rights." It accused the Americans of "covering up for
the slaughters which have been perpetrated by Israel over the
years, especially the Qana massacre."
</P>
<P>
The Christian-owned Nida-Al-Watan said that the U.S. was
"never a real Middle East peace broker and Lebanon never
expected the Americans to reward it for anything."
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Defense Minister Mohsen Dalloul accused the U.S. of
being consistently biased in favor of Israel while other Arab
countries are punished on the pretext of failing to carry out
U.N. resolutions."
</P>
<P>
In a dialogue with local resident in the Shiite-populated
Beqaa Valley in eastern Lebanon at the weekend, Dalloul further
said that by describing the resistance movement against the
Israeli forces in south Lebanon as "terrorism", the U.S was
"provoking and challenging Arab feelings." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
