<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Leader Meets German Foreign Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Li Ruihuan, chairman of the National
Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference, reiterated today that China will never seek
hegemonism. He called the "China threat" totally groundless.
</P>
<P>
The "China threat" is a pretext fabricated by a handful persons to
contain China, said Li while meeting with German Foreign Minister
Klaus Kinkel at the State Guesthouse here.
</P>
<P>
Those people disliked seeing a China on the road chosen by
itself, a rapidly developing China, for fear of a powerful China
to hinder their hegemonist practice, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Since 1840, China had suffered a lot from foreign imperialist
aggression and humiliation and had paid a heavy cost in blood in
resistance to such aggression and humiliation, the Chinese leader
said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the Chinese people hated and opposed hegemonism, and
China would never harm other nations by practicing hegemonism.
</P>
<P>
China will concentrate on developing its economy and improving
the living standards of its people because it remains a developing
country with a backward economy and culture, and needs to struggle
50 to 100 years to reach the level of moderately developed
countries, said Li.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese leader pointed out that even if China becomes
prosperous and strong in the future, it will not bully and
threaten others.
</P>
<P>
Late Chinese leaders, Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping, told the
Chinese people that China would never practice hegemonism, and
pose as a world leader, Li said.
</P>
<P>
History has demonstrated that all those who practice
hegemonism, whether globally or regionally, come to an sticky end,
Li said, citing Adolf Hitler and Tojo Hideki as examples.
</P>
<P>
On Sino-German relations, Li said there exist no problems left
over from history between the two countries and they share
extensive common interests.
</P>
<P>
He said the two countries should all the more treasure the
current situation of bilateral relations established after many
twists and turns.
</P>
<P>
Li repeated China's appreciation for Germany's wise decision
not to participate in the anti-China motion at this year's session
of the United Nations Human Rights Commission.
</P>
<P>
China has always considered and handled issues on its ties with
Germany from a strategic point of view. It is willing to establish
with Germany a long-term, stable, comprehensively cooperative ties
which are oriented to the 21st century, the chairman said.
</P>
<P>
In response, Kinkel said as a major world power, a permanent
member of the UN security council, and the largest burgeoning
market in the world, China is playing an important role in
international affairs.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that maintaining good German-China relations is in
the fundamental interests of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel also said that it is very wise for China, the most
populous country in the world, to give top priority to economic
development and to work hard for the basic needs of its people.
</P>
<P>
Both the German and Chinese economies have their own strong
points and are highly complementary, he said.
</P>
<P>
Germany hopes economic and trade cooperation between the two
countries will be further grow, he said.
</P>
<P>
The German foreign minister repeated that Germany would stick
to its position that Taiwan and Tibet were inalienable parts of
China.
</P>
<P>
Li arrived here today from Berlin to continue his seven-day
goodwill visit. He is scheduled to meet German President Roman
Herzog, Chancellor Helmut Kohl and the president of the Bundestag,
the lower house of the German parliament, Rita Suessmuth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
