<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 13 Beaches in Cyprus Awarded Blue Flags </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Thirteen Cypriot beaches were
awarded the Blue Flag this year by the Foundation for
Environmental Education in Europe (FEE), a Cypriot environmental
official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Michael Ierides, President of Cyprus Marine Environmental
Protection Association (CYMEPA), told reporters that another five
beaches in Cyprus have been awarded pilot flags, not because
they are lacking in cleanliness or facilities, but because not
enough chemical analyses of the water were carried out
throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first year Cyprus has been granted full Blue
Flags, as last year we only had 11 pilot flags," Ierides said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that this year 23 applications had been submitted to
CYMEPA, the national operator for the Blue Flags, but three were
rejected by the eight-member National Jury, made up of
representatives of the Health Ministry, Environment Department,
the Cyprus Tourism Organization, the Local Authorities and the
Consumers' Association.
</P>
<P>
He explained that these three beaches were not given the Blue
flag because their facilities were not yet completed.
</P>
<P>
According to Ierides, a total of 1,809 beaches in Europe were
awarded the Blue Flags by the FEE, which is a non-governmental
organization consisting of 18 European countries.
</P>
<P>
The FEE has 26 criteria that have to be met to award a beach
with the Blue Flag. They divide into three categories, namely the
quality of the water and the beach, its management, security and
environmental education.
</P>
<P>
This eastern Mediterranean island launched a "Clean-up Cyprus"
campaign this month, which is aimed at making the island a more
competitive tourist destination.
</P>
<P>
More than 2 million foreign tourists visit the island every
year, earning the country about 1.6 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
