<HEADLINE> Foreign Ministers of Balkan Countries Meeting in Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 9 (Xinhua) -- A two-day conference of foreign
ministers from southeast Europe today opened in Thessaloniki,
northern Greece.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in his opening speech, Greek Foreign Minister
Theodoros Pangalos urged his Balkan counterparts to work toward
the establishment of broad cooperation aimed at consolidating
political stability and economic development in the region.
</P>
<P>
He said that the progress achieved since a similar meeting in
Sofia last year was significant but "below our true capabilities."
</P>
<P>
Noting that the countries represented by ministers at the
conference shared the same ideals on which the European Union (EU)
was founded, he intimated that they should work toward the
construction of a similar union of their own.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed the need for strengthening economic ties
between the countries of the region at a bilateral, multilateral
and regional level, as well as the implementation of specific
programs for the development of the region's infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Pangalos recalled the proposal put forward by Greece in
February calling for the long-term solution of problems arising
from countries in the region in the present phase of their
transition to a market economy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis today hailed the
conference as "a decisive step" towards further progress in
cooperation between the countries of the region.
</P>
<P>
He said in a message to the conference that following the
changes which have taken place in the region, countries in the
region must seek new challenges and take advantage of new
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
He added that the successful outcome of the conference will be
"a milestone" in the development of the conference for stability,
security and cooperation in southeast Europe.
</P>
<P>
During the conference, the participants will examine issues
concerning broader political cooperation in fields such as the
protection of the environment, the promotion of humanitarian,
social and cultural cooperation and common action to fight
organized crime.
</P>
<P>
They will also discuss the development of economic cooperation
between the Balkan countries and initiatives aimed at regional
cooperation in southeast Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
