<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean Insurance Firms Rush to Southeast Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 9 (Xinhua) -- South Korean insurance firms are
rushing to take a piece of vast insurance markets in Southeast
Asia, China and other countries in Asia, the country's insurance
industry sources said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia, Thailand and China are targeted as the biggest
potential market for South Korean insurance firms which already
maintain offices in these countries.
</P>
<P>
Latest government statistics showed, South Korean insurers are
operating more than 70 overseas branches and offices, compared to
41 foreign insurers in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Samsung Life Insurance Co. has agreed to set up a joint venture
insurance firm in Thailand in partnership with three Thai
companies. With 25 percent of the total holdings for each
company, the signing took place several days ago in Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
Samsung Life Co. also plans to upgrade its branch in Singapore
to a local incorporated company so as to make it engage in
insurance business there.
</P>
<P>
Another firm, Daehan Life Co., is trying to open branch offices
in Hong Kong and Malaysia to secure a foothold for its business in
Asia.
</P>
<P>
In addition, non-life insurance firms, plan to make inroads
into Southeast Asia, particularly in Indonesia, with a plan
targeting many South Koreans working there as potential buyers.
</P>
<P>
Samsung Fire Co. has entered into an agreement last February to
set up a joint venture non-life insurance company with an
Indonesian insurance company at a total investment of 7 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
LG Fire Co. will set up a local subsidiary in August in
Indonesia, along with Hyundai Marine Insurance Co., Dongbu Fire
Co. and Tongyang Fire Co..
</P>
<P>
Aware of the enormous growth potential of China's insurance
market, South Korean insurance firms, including Samsung Fire
Insurance Co., LG Insurance Co. and Hyundai Marine, are now
vigorously pushing to secure footholds in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
