<HEADLINE> Ireland's Ahern Says Minority Government Will Last </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Ireland's Fianna Fail party leader
Bertie Ahern, set to become the country's new Prime Minister after
winning a narrow election victory, said in Dublin today that his
minority government will last.
</P>
<P>
Ahern, whose opposition alliance won 81 of the 166 parliament
seats, dismissed press speculation of holding early elections,
saying that he was determined his minority government would last
its five-year term, press reports from Dublin said.
</P>
<P>
"The aim will be to have a four or five year government,"
Ahern said, adding he hoped independent parties, on whose support
he will have to court in a bid to achieve a parliament majority,
would be mindful of the need for political stability.
</P>
<P>
"I would hope most of them would be concerned about how long
the new parliament can last. We have to get an arrangement that
will last in the longer term," he added.
</P>
<P>
On the new government's views on the single European currency,
outgoing Irish Finance Minister Ruair Quinn, attending an European
Union Finance Ministers meeting in Luxembourg, said today he was
confident the new government would give the same backing to
European economic and monetary union (EMU).
</P>
<P>
"I hope that they will maintain the progress we have put in
place and I would be reasonably confident that by and large they
will," he said. "The commitment of the Irish government to the
single currency project -- the incoming government -- will be the
same as the outgoing government." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
