<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zanzibar Acts to Improve Economic Infrastructure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The Zanzibar government
planned to enhance the country's economic infrastructure by
mobilizing investors under the proposed build-cooperate-transfer
(BOT) strategy.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Ahmed Abdulrahman, principal secretary
in the president's office who was opening a three-day workshop on
infrastructure development through BOT in the town of Zanzibar
today.
</P>
<P>
He said the system would provide a lasting solution to the
setting up of a sound infrastructural base for the Isles.
</P>
<P>
Under the BOT system, investors would be allowed to open
projects and operate them for a certain period before handing
over to the government.
</P>
<P>
Abdulrahman told the participants, most of them directors and
managers of companies, that due to limited resources, the
government was unable to provide necessary economic
infrastructure and would therefore welcome better economic
strategies to solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
He said the government would continue to put emphasis on
intrastructure facilities because that was one of the factors
that would attract investments.
</P>
<P>
The principal secretary said the BOT concept has been adopted
with great success by a number of developing countries such as
India, Pakistan, Turkey, Malaysia and the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
He noted that bridges, highways, power plants, port and
airport facilities have been established and the number of
investors increased by adopting the BOT strategy.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that the BOT concept is one of the tools that would
help Zanzibar to improve its infrastructure facilities," He said.
</P>
<P>
Abdulrahman said the introduction of BOT concept was part of
the government's commitment to create a favorable and predictable
investment atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
The workshop was co-sponsored by the United Nations
Development Program and the United Nations Industrial Development
Organization in collaboration with the Zanzibar government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-09 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Rules out Early Resumption of Diplomatic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez
Boueiz ruled out here today an early resumption of diplomatic ties
with Iraq, saying economic and political relations are different.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question on a resumption of relations with Iraq at
a news conference in his office, the foreign minister said that
"it is still too early to talk about the diplomatic relations
despite that economic contacts between the private sectors of the
two countries have begun."
</P>
<P>
Underlining a separation between the economic and political
links, the foreign minister pointed out that the private sector
in Lebanon "is free and independent and it has the right to
cooperate with Iraq according to their direct and common
interests and we are not against the cooperation on this level."
</P>
<P>
He confirmed that the Iraqis have repeatedly expressed a
desire for a resumption of relations with Lebanon since the Iraqi
embassy in Beirut was closed some three years ago.
</P>
<P>
Jacques Sarraf, chairman of the Lebanese Industrialists
Association, expected at the weekend that Lebanon will "soon"
resume diplomatic ties with Iraq to make convenient the export of
Lebanese goods to that country.
</P>
<P>
Sarraf, who visited Baghdad in March heading a powerful
delegation of Lebanese businessmen, said that the Lebanese
government "will coordinate Damascus on this issue."
</P>
<P>
Lebanon broke off diplomatic ties with Iraq in April 1994,
over the killing of an Iraqi opposition leader, Talib Suheli
Al-Tamimi in Beirut in which the Lebanese government accused
Iraqi diplomats of being involved.
</P>
<P>
Even before that, the relations between the two countries had
become tense when Iraq backed Lebanese former army general Michel
Aoun in his failed war against Syrian forces in Lebanon in 1989.
</P>
<P>
In a move interpreted as a sign to show intentions to improve
the relations, the Lebanese authorities released three Iraqis in
January, who were considered the perpetrators of Al-Tamimi's
murder. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
