<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> APEC Environment Ministerial Meeting Opens in Toronto </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TORONTO, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The Environment Ministerial Meeting
of Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) opened here today in
another bid to develop practical solutions to the region's
environmental challenges.
</P>
<P>
"Our goal at this meeting is to find better ways of putting the
principle of sustainable development into practice," said Sergio
Marchi, chair of the meeting and environment minister of Canada.
</P>
<P>
The three-day ministerial meeting will have two tasks, Marchi
said at today's opening plenary.
</P>
<P>
"The first is to develop an Action Plan that contains practical
solutions to help create more sustainable urban areas, more
sustainable marine environments and cleaner production methods in
each of our economies," he said.
</P>
<P>
The second is "to send a clear 'sustainable development'
message" to APEC Economic Leaders when they meet in Vancouver in
November.
</P>
<P>
"The message is that all our economies must redouble their
efforts to make sustainable development the overarching objective
by integrating our economic, development, social and trade
agendas," he noted.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, APEC ministers will also have a chance to
hear the views and recommendations of the Business Leaders and
Local Authorities Forum, as well as the Environmental Youth
Caucus.
</P>
<P>
A final joint statement on sustainable development strategies
and actions will be developed by the APEC ministers to take
forward to the APEC Economic Leaders' Meeting.
</P>
<P>
Ministers and their representatives from all 18 APEC economies
are participating in the ministerial meeting.
</P>
<P>
The 18 APEC economies are Australia, Brunei Darussalam, Canada,
Chile, the People's Republic of China, Hong Kong, Indonesia,
Japan, the Republic of Korea, Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Papua
New Guinea, the Republic of the Philippines, Singapore, Chinese
Taipei, Thailand and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Economies in the Asia-Pacific region are among the most
dynamic, fastest-growing economies in the world.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, these 18 economies had a combined gross domestic
product of more than 16 trillion U.S. dollars, about half of the
world's annual output. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kok, Van Den Broek Arrive in Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Dutch Prime Minister Wim Kok and
Foreign Minister Hans Van Den Broek arrived here today as part of
a tour of European capitals before a European Union (EU) summit in
Amsterdam on June 16-17.
</P>
<P>
During their one-day visit, they will hold talks with Greek
Prime Minister Costas Simitis and Foreign Minister Theodoros
Pangalos.
</P>
<P>
After Greece, they will fly to Paris to meet with French
leaders.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands currently holds the rotating EU presidency
until the end of June. 
</P>
