<HEADLINE> Thirtieth Anniversary of 1967 Arab-Israeli War Observed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 9 (Xinhua) -- A special meeting of the
Committee on the Exercise of the Inalienable Rights of the
Palestinian People was convened here today to observe the
thirtieth anniversary of the Arab-Israeli War of June 1967.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the meeting, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said
that the United Nations had always played a central role in
assisting the parties in their efforts to reach a negotiated
settlement.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the Declaration of the Principles on Interim
Self-Government arrangements by Israel and the Palestine
Liberation Organization on September 1993 was a major breakthrough
in those efforts, Annan said.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the beginning of the Oslo peace process also opened
major new opportunities for supportive action by the United
Nations. Those included the creation of a special mechanism to
coordinate international assistance and the appointment of a
United Nations Special Coordinator in the Occupied Territories to
serve as a focal point for all United Nations agencies and
programs operating on the ground.
</P>
<P>
The General-Secretary said that he had been encouraged by the
agreement on Hebron and it was an important achievement that
should pave the way for further progress towards full
implementation of the process envisaged at Oslo.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed deep concern that despite the appeals from
the international society, the government of Israel decided to
proceed with the construction at Jabal Abu/Har Homa and called on
the parties to do their utmost to find mutually acceptable
solution, and proceed with the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
