<HEADLINE> S. Leonean Workers Continue Strike Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Government employees in Freetown,
capital of Sierra Leone, continued to stay away from jobs today
despite coup leaders' threat to sack them.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here said government employees, company
clerks and factory workers stood outside their working places on
the pavement, refusing to go back to work on the grounds of
non-payment and continuous looting by the coup soldiers.
</P>
<P>
"Last night the army looted the few remaining electric fans,"
said a clerk at the Freetown Magistrates' Court.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of shoppers descended on three groceries in downtown
areas to stock up on rice, sugar and flour while heavily armed
soldiers guarded the shops to prevent breakout of quarrels and
fights.
</P>
<P>
While stocks of shops were running out, there was no immediate
prospect of restocking. A senior harbor official said several
boats carrying rice and other foodstuffs had been diverted to
neighboring Guinea despite their scheduled arrival at Freetown.
</P>
<P>
The silent strike has been maintained for consecutive two
weeks since the widely condemned May 25 coup overthrew the
civilian government led by President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
A statement of the military junta, repeatedly broadcasted on
the state radio since Saturday, warned that anyone absent from
work without a valid reason would be sacked.
</P>
<P>
The coup leaders have sent a delegation to other west African
countries to explain reasons for the coup which triggered off a
military action by the sub-regiona's peacekeeping force, led by
Nigeria, to restore power of the ousted President Kabbah.
</P>
</TEXT>
