<HEADLINE> Egypt: Gap Unbridged Between Palestinians, Israelis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Despite the Palestinian-Israeli
expert meeting on Sunday, the gap separating the two sides remains
in place, Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said here today.
</P>
<P>
Moussa told reporters that the Cairo meeting designed to pave
way for renewing the full-scale Palestinian-Israeli talks has
failed to clear major obstacles but he stopped short of specifying
the details.
</P>
<P>
"The situation requires further efforts in the coming days,"
he said, adding that another expert meeting in Israel on Thursday
between the two sides is part of those efforts.
</P>
<P>
Israeli and Palestinian negotiators met here on Sunday night
for the first time in nearly three months since the peace talks
were paralyzed when Israel began construction on a new Jewish
settlement in the disputed Arab East Jerusalem in March.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian top diplomat waved off the statement of European
Mideast envoy Miguel Moratinos about giving Egyptian efforts a
deadline for moving forward the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt rejects any dictation to it. There are no such a thing
as definitive deadlines for any topic, but rather a reasonable
time framework for any political action undertaken by any party,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said the European role in the Middle East is important
and Europe can engage in cooperation (with other parties in the
peace process) on an equal basis "without piling pressure."
</P>
<P>
Palestinian officials have confirmed that the fate of the
housing project was discussed in the Sunday talks.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat voiced
his sorrow today that Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu
has not issued instructions for halting settlement construction in
Har Homa in East Jerusalem and other areas.
</P>
<P>
Israel has reportedly hatched a face-saving compromise under
which it will slow down the Har Homa construction to a near halt
to allow the resumption of talks with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
But Netanyahu today denied the existence of such a plan and
said the construction will continue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
