<HEADLINE> Turkish Troops Flies to U.S. for Joint Maneuvers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- A group of 50 Turkish officers and
soldiers today flew to the United States to participate in a
multinational military exercises from June 11 to July 4.
</P>
<P>
The Cooperative Nugget maneuvers will be held in Fort Polk
Joint Military Training Center in Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that Turkey sends its land forces to
overseas military exercises.
</P>
<P>
The joint maneuvers is reportedly aimed at strengthening
military coordination among the participant countries for
regional stability in the Balkans and neighboring states.
</P>
<P>
Besides Turkey, the United States, Canada, Belgium and other
Partnership for Peace countries will also take part in the
military exercises.
</P>
<P>
Greece, a traditional rival country with Turkey, made a
U-turn last week to withdraw from the joint maneuvers, saying
that it would not participate in the drills with a Turkish
military unit.
</P>
<P>
Athens usually does not participate in any NATO military
exercises organized in or by Turkey, although both of them are
NATO member countries.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece have long been at odds due to differences
over a number of sensitive issues, including the Agean Sea
sovereignty, mineral rights as well as the Cyprus problem.
</P>
</TEXT>
