<HEADLINE> Cook Confident of Securing Good Deal at EU Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 9 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook
said today that Britain was likely to secure a good deal at the
European Union (EU) summit to be held in Amsterdam next week.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at parliament this afternoon, Cook said that the new
Labor government, which won a landslide victory on a May 1
election, was poised to get positive results from the EU summit
because of its constructive stance taken on European policy.
</P>
<P>
Cook explained that the Labor government had already
re-established Britain as a leading player in Europe because it
had given up the previous Conservative government's
confrontational strategy on Europe.
</P>
<P>
"Precisely because this government is not shouting `No' to
everything out of prejudice, we are listened to with respect when
we do say `No' to issues that threaten Britain's national
interests," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
On the EU summit, Cook said he was confident of reaching
agreement with Britain's EU partners on border controls, fighting
against fraud in EU member states, reform of the Council of
Ministers and the common foreign and security policy.
</P>
<P>
"We can return from Amsterdam not just having done a good deal
for Britain but having obtained a better deal for Britain that the
previous government could have hoped to achieve," Cook said.
</P>
</TEXT>
