<HEADLINE> Chirac Obtains Promise of Cease-Fire from Congolese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 9 (Xinhua) -- President Jacques Chirac today
obtained from President Pascal Lissouba of the Congo Republic and
former President Denis Sassou N'Guesso an "agreement of principle"
on a cease-fire in the capital Brazzaville, the French
presidential office announced this evening.
</P>
<P>
Chirac talked on telephone today with Lissouba, Sassou N'Guesso
and Gabonese President Omar Bongo about the crisis in the Congo
Republic, and he used the "same language" to urge the conflicting
sides of Congo to implement a cease-fire, said presidential
spokeswoman Catherine Colonna.
</P>
<P>
"There is no military solution to a political problem. One
cannot but condemn the actual behaviors. It is unacceptable to
talk about war," said Chirac in his telephone conversation with
Lissouba and Sassou N'Guesso.
</P>
<P>
Chirac asked both men to arrange a cease-fire as quickly as
possible and to accept the mediation by Bongo to find a peaceful
solution to the conflict in the Congo Republic.
</P>
<P>
Both Lissouba and Sassou N'Guesso agreed in principle to the
request of Chirac, said Colonna.
</P>
<P>
France today sent a reinforcement of 800 soldiers to the Congo
Republic to protect the French nationals there, after one French
soldier was killed Saturday night when trying to help foreigners
evacuate from a hotel in Brazzaville.
</P>
<P>
This added the number of French troops deployed in the Congo
Republic to 1,250.
</P>
<P>
Some French nationals who have fled Congo said that anti-French
feeling was on the rise in Congo.
</P>
<P>
Government troops and the militiamen supporting N'Guesso fought
for a fifth consecutive day today in Brazzaville, as both sides
held the other side responsible for the violence, in which
hundreds of civilians were reportedly killed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
