<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IFC Invests in China's Petrochemical Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC) today announced the investment of 46.7 million
U.S. dollars equivalent in Suzhou Huasu Plastic Co., Ltd.
</P>
<P>
The new company, located in the Liujia Port Economic
Development Zone in Suzhou, Jiangsu Province, will operate a plant
capable of producing 100,000 tons of polyvinyl chloride (PVC)
resin per year and a 24,000 ton per year film calendering
facility.
</P>
<P>
PVC is a major commodity plastic used in industrial and
consumer products such as pipes, fittings, wire cables and
bottles. The calendering process converts PVC compounds into PVC
film and sheets.
</P>
<P>
The new company will be the first petrochemicals joint venture
project with U.S. and Norway companies in Suzhou providing a
vehicle for the transfer of modern technology and know-how. The 90
million dollar plant is scheduled to be completed in early 1999.
It will import vinyl chloride monomer, which is the main raw
material for PVC, but its products will be sold in the domestic
and overseas markets.
</P>
<P>
IFC's financing package includes a 22 million dollar loan for
its own account, a 2.5 million dollar equity investment and a 22.2
million dollar loan for the account of participating banks. The
Norwegian Agency for Development Cooperation is co-financing the
project with a 3.8 million dollar equivalent loan.
</P>
<P>
IFC is a member of the World Bank Group and also the largest
multilateral source of equity and loan financing for private
sector projects in developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kissinger: Revoking MFN Risks Confrontation With China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Former Secretary of State Henry
Kissinger has said that revoking the Most Favored Nation (MFN)
trade status for China was not in the U.S. national interest as it
would lead to a political confrontation with China.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with CBS's "One on One" program last Friday,
released today, Kissinger said the MFN status was in fact the
normal trade treatment as "there are only six nations in the whole
world that don't have MFN status."
</P>
<P>
"So if it is rejected, it would mean that the most populous
nation in the world is put into separate status. And it's
equivalent to a political confrontation with China," said the
former secretary of state, who was instrumental in thawing ice
between the United States and China in the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
Revoking the MFN for China was not "in the national interest
because the relations with China are essential or important for
stability in Asia," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kissinger rebuked someone's preach of "China threat," saying it
was "running a huge risk of talking ourselves into a demonology of
China as a madly aggressive country."
</P>
<P>
"China is growing at the rate of 10 percent a year. That sounds
formidable, and it is. But we have to remember that 10 percent of
China's growth is less than 1 percent of ours. So actually the gap
is increasing in our favor," he said.
</P>
<P>
As regards the future of Hong Kong after its returning to China
on July 1, Kissinger believed that the Chinese would keep the "one
country, two systems" principle going "because it is essential for
them as a bridge to Taiwan, to show that you can have one country,
two systems, and because it is essential also for the economy of
Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
"They will not want to have that economy disintegrate just
after it returns to China," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kissinger predicted that Hong Kong would have a smooth
transition, and "nothing will happen in the first week" after the
transfer of power.
</P>
<P>
"Unless it is provoked by the presence of so much attention and
6,000 newsmen wanting to generate stories," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Set New Highs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Stocks on Wall Street pushed
further into record highes today, briefly boosting the Dow Jones
industrial average above 7,500 for the first time.
</P>
<P>
The Dow rose by 42.72 points to 7,478.50, its second straight
record close. The blue-chip barometer bobbed above 7,500 several
times during the session before retreating during the last hour.
The Dow -- up about 1,000 points, or 16 percent, for the year --
first broke above 6,000 in October and 7,000 in February
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a nearly 4-to-3
margin on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 465.57
million shares as against 488.40 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
Broader indicators also set new highs.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 4.92 to 862.93, and
the NYSE's composite index rose 2.04 to 450.17, with both measures
adding to Friday's record highs.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index rose 7.33 to 1,412.17, its first new
high in eight sessions. The American Stock Exchange composite
index rose 4.92 to 619.57, setting its first new high in more than
a year.
</P>
<P>
The market was not affected by a weak bond session in which
long-term interest rates rose. Some major corporate deals also
added to investor enthusiasm, according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
Those deals included an agreement by Microsoft to invest 1
billion U.S. dollars in Comcast, the nation's fourth-largest cable
company. BankAmerica, meanwhile, agreed to buy the investment firm
Robertson Stephens for up to 540 million U.S. dollars; and Safeco,
a West Coast property-casualty insurer, agreed to pay 2.82 billion
U.S. dollars for the Midwestern insurance firm American States
Financial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
