<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Achieves Strong Growth in High-Tech Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's domestic exports of
high-tech products increased by about 16 percent per annum between
1990 and 1996 to reach about 39.3 billion US dollars in 1996, the
Singapore Trade Development Board (TDB) said today.
</P>
<P>
This is higher than the corresponding growth rate of 11 percent
per annum achieved for total non-oil domestic exports, the TDB
said.
</P>
<P>
The TDB said the share of high-tech products as a percentage of
the non-oil domestic exports has risen from 52 percent in 1990 to
65 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"This reflects the success of Singapore's efforts to
restructure and upgrade its economy to one based on high-tech and
high value-added industries," it said.
</P>
<P>
The TDB also noted that in the period of 1990-95, Singapore's
share of all high-technology exports by the four Newly
Industrialized Economies (NIEs) was the highest at 35.4 percent.
The NIEs are Singapore, South Korea, Hong Kong and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
A comparison by products category showed that Singapore was
ahead of those three NIEs for domestic exports of bio-technology,
advanced materials, opto-electronics, and information and
communication products in 1995, it said.
</P>
<P>
However, Singapore was behind South Korea and Taiwan for the
exports of electronics and flexible manufactures. And it came in
second behind South Korea for its domestic exports of aerospace
products.
</P>
<P>
The TDB said it would step up its efforts to "safeguard and
expand" market access for Singapore's high technology exports. And
it would assist high technology companies to penetrate new markets
and make inroads into existing ones.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
