<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan, Russia Seek Good Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto expressed the wish today that Japanese-Russian relations
could be fully normalized by the signing of a peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
He was meeting Russia's First Deputy Prime Minister Boris
Nemtsov here.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto said he would discuss with Russian President Boris
Yeltsin ways for a comprehensive improvement of Japanese-Russian
ties, at the Denver summit scheduled for later this month. He
would also notify Yeltsin whether he would accept Yeltsin's
invitation to visit Moscow this year.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister hoped the two countries could work hard for
a quick solution to disputes over the safety of Japanese fishing
boats operating around four Russian-held islands off Japan's
northernmost main island of Hokkaido.
</P>
<P>
Nemtsov, who arrived here Monday for a three-day visit, handed
Yeltsin's personal letter to Hashimoto at the prime minister's
official residence.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, Yeltsin said no issues could not be solved
between Russia and Japan and the two nations' basic interests were
close or unanimous.
</P>
<P>
The Russian president repeated his proposal that the two states
hold a summit every year to strengthen bilateral political
dialogue and settle issues.
</P>
<P>
Tokyo and Moscow have held a series of talks since March 1995
following incidents in which Russian patrol boats fired at
Japanese fishing vessels in waters near the disputed islands.
</P>
<P>
The decades-old row over the islands has prevented the two
countries from signing a peace treaty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
