<HEADLINE> Nepal to Help Private Sector Promote Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Prime Minister Lokendra
Bahadur Chand said here today that the government has started
organizing training programs to provide management expertise and
manpower to the private sector in order to promote exports and
strengthen their competitive capabilities.
</P>
<P>
While addressing the 31st annual general meeting of the
Federation of Nepalese Chamber of Commerce and Industry (FNCCI),
Chand said it is the need of the hour to move ahead promotional
activities to attract investment in Nepal by making the
government's concepts of open, liberal and free market more
practical and suitable to the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Chand noted that as new challenges will be faced in the
international trade sector at the beginning of the 21st century,
close relationship should be maintained between the government and
the private sector by realizing the fact that we will be compelled
to work in accordance with the norms and values developed by the
World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
He said the governments and the private sectors of the South
Asian countries should make necessary preparations to build the
capability of facing the challenges and converting the available
opportunities into benefits in the process of translating
preferential trade into free trade between the South Asian
countries.
</P>
<P>
Expressing his commitment to provide maximum attractive
benefits to broaden the scope for investment by increasing
domestic savings, Chand said the government is flexible in
improving and refining the policies if they are found inadequate
for setting up business enterprises and developing a sense of
security for the investments being made by national and foreign
investors.  
</P>
