<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Government to Raise Water Charges by 4 folds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore government has
decided to raise water charges by four folds over the next three
years to get Singaporeans to treat water as a precious and
strategic resource, and make water conservation a way of life,
Acting Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong announced today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Lee noted the steady 4.7
percent rise in water consumption in Singapore over the past ten
years. At the present rate, Singapore would be short of water by
year 2011 if the first water agreement with Malaysia was not
renewed.
</P>
<P>
The two Water Agreements between the Public Utilities Board
(PUB) of Singapore and the Johor State Government of Malaysia were
signed in 1961 and 1962. In 1965, when Singapore became
independent, the Malaysian Federal government specifically
guaranteed these two Water Agreements in the Separation Agreement.
</P>
<P>
According to the Separation Agreement, the two Water Agreements
will expire in 2011 and 2061 respectively. Water supply from
Malaysia accounts for about 50 percent of Singapore's water
consumption.
</P>
<P>
"We must revise the present pricing structure. Water
conservation must apply equally to all households and firms. As
water is a strategic resource, the first drop is precious," the
acting prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government's long term objective is to
restructure the water tariffs and water conservation tax into
uniform flat rates, and that the adjustments to the water tariffs,
water conservation tax, and waterborne fees will be phased in over
four annual increments of roughly equal dollar amounts, starting
from July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The new rates will apply each year from the August cycle of
meter readings and the price of water will be raised to about two
Singapore dollars (about 1.4 US dollars at current exchange rate)
per cubic meter by the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
Although the financial impact of these adjustments will be
significant, Lee stressed however that this is necessary for the
revisions to have an impact on consumers, and to get them to
conserve water.
</P>
<P>
But he also said that the government would offset the increases
for lower income households with utilities rebates and higher
subsidies.
</P>
<P>
The government was doing its best to ensure that Singapore was
able to cater to its own water needs, he said. This, as he
disclosed, included concluding water agreements with Indonesia,
building desalination plants, and exploiting water sources to the
limit.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
