<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Meets South African Vice-Foreign Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier and Foreign
Minister Qian Qichen, in a meeting with South African Vice-foreign
Minister Aziz Pahad here today, said that normalization of
Sino-South African ties would benefit both sides and create
conditions necessary for friendly cooperation in politics, the
economy, and diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
Qian expressed his pleasure with the progress in negotiations
on establishing Sino-South African diplomatic relations, and his
appreciation for South Africa's "wise decision" to "sever
diplomatic links" with Taiwan. Normalization of China-South Africa
relations is in the two countries' interests, he said.
</P>
<P>
African countries became independent one after another and have
mastered their own destiny since World War Two, Qian said, and
these countries are now striving for economic independence.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the belief that African countries will develop
vigorously and win economic independence in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Qian briefed Pahad on China's independent foreign policy of
peace and voiced his admiration for South Africa's increasing
positive role in African affairs.
</P>
<P>
Pahad expressed his appreciation for China's dedication to the
just struggle of the South African people and its important role
in international affairs. The normalization of South Africa-China
relations will be conducive to democracy and development in South
Africa, he said, and that his country is expecting cooperation
with China in international affairs.
</P>
<P>
He said he believes economic cooperation between the two
countries will also increase with the normalization of bilateral
ties.
</P>
<P>
Pahad is here to discuss establishing Sino-South African
diplomatic relations. Chinese Vice-Foreign Ministry Tian Zengpei
met with him yesterday and Chinese assistant Foreign Minister Ji
Peiding discussed establishing diplomatic ties between the two
countries and issues of common interest with him.
</P>
<P>
It is learnt that in light of South Africa's requirement, the
Chinese side has agreed to make temporary arrangements for the
status of the South African consulate general and other South
African interests in Hong Kong for the period from July 1 to the
establishment of Sino-South African diplomatic ties. The South
African side has expressed its thanks for China's friendly
attitude.
</P>
<P>
Chinese minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation Wu
Yi also met with Pahad here today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
