<HEADLINE> Soeharto: Car Policy Talks Should Not Damage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
today ordered the continuation of the talks with Japan, the United
States and European Union (EU) on Indonesia's national car program
without impairing the national interests.
</P>
<P>
Industry and Trade Minister Tunky Ariwibowo met with Soeharto
to report on his talks with the Japanese government and EU
concerning the national car program.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters after the meeting that Japan has submitted
some proposals, including a reduction on import duty.
</P>
<P>
The national car program, launched in February 1996, grants
tariff and luxury sales tax exemptions to national cars on
condition that their local content rises to 60 percent in three
years.
</P>
<P>
However, only a joint venture between Pt. Timor Putra Nasional
and South Korean Kia motors is qualified to produce national car
until 1999.
</P>
<P>
Japan and the EU have taken Indonesia's national car policy to
the World Trade Organization's (WTO) dispute settlement body. The
United States has also protested the policy but is still trying to
resolve the dispute through bilateral negotiations. The trio
claimed that Indonesia's car policy is discriminatory and against
multilateral trade rules.
</P>
<P>
The government, Tunky said, is preparing to continue talks with
the three groups on the national car dispute, but he did not
reveal the timing for the talks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
