<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Court Upholds Ban on Charter Change Move </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Supreme Court today
upheld an earlier ruling prohibiting a non-governmental group from
proceeding its bid to change the Constitution to extend the term
of President Fidel Ramos.
</P>
<P>
In a vote of seven to six, the court rejected the petition
filed by the People's Initiatives for Reform, Modernization and
Action (PIRMA), a pro-Ramos group, seeking the reversal of the
tribunal's March 19 decision.
</P>
<P>
In a resolution issued after the voting, the court said the
motion lacked "sufficient cogency to persuade the requisite
majority of the court to modify or reverse the decision of March"
and was "denied with finality."
</P>
<P>
Thirteen of the 15 justices of the high bench participated in
the voting, with the other two being on leave.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after learning the court's decision, Executive
Secretary Ruben Torres, a close aide to Ramos, expressed his
disappointment over the ruling.
</P>
<P>
"We hoped that the people's right to petition through a
signature campaign to amend the constitution would be upheld by
the Supreme Court, but we respect the Supreme Court's decision in
this regard," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Torres also denied persistent reports that officials at the
Presidential Palace attempted to influence the positive outcome of
the court decision.
</P>
<P>
The court's March 19 ruling said that there is no enabling law
which provides for a people's initiative for charter change.
</P>
<P>
It stopped the Commission on Elections from entertaining
PIRMA's petition to hold a plebiscite on constitution changes and
banned PIRMA leaders from further gathering signatures needed for
a people's initiative to amend the charter.
</P>
<P>
The PIRMA, launched late last year by Ramos' supporters, has
sought to remove the term limits for all government officials,
including that of Ramos, by changing the country's 1987
constitution.
</P>
<P>
The existing charter, which was promulgated after the downfall
of former dictatorial president Fernand Marcos, provides for a
single six-year term for the president.
</P>
<P>
Ramos himself has repeatedly indicated that he will step down
when his term of office expires in June 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece, Russia Call for Increased Cooperation in Balkans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Greece and Russia today agreed in a
joint initiative to strengthen cooperation in promoting peace and
stability in southeast Europe.
</P>
<P>
The pact called for a meeting late next year by representatives
of southeast European countries with the participation of the
permanent members of the U.N. Security Council, the European Union
(EU) and other international organizations.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was announced by Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros
Pangalos and Russian Foreign Undersecretary Nicolai Afanasievski
in the northern Greek port city of Thessaloniki.
</P>
<P>
In a joint communique, both sides urged the Balkan foreign
ministers attending the two-day Thessaloniki conference to support
the initiative.
</P>
<P>
A working meeting of senior officials this Autumn would be the
"first step" in preparing the 1998 meeting, to be followed by
meetings of ministers of foreign affairs, energy and transports,
and commerce, the communique said.
</P>
<P>
Pangalos said that the initiative would give "a broader
perspective to closer Balkan cooperation." Afanasievski hailed the
Thessaloniki meeting as a "great success."  
</P>
</TEXT>
