Japan later this month, the first visit of its kind in 103 years,
the Japanese Defense Agency said today.
</P>
<P>
The 7,600-ton destroyer, which belongs to the Pacific Fleet of
the Russian naval forces, will enter the Port of Tokyo on June 27
and stay for four days.
</P>
<P>
The Maritime Staff Office said that the last port call by a
Russian warship was in 1894 when a vessel came for the ceremony of
Emperor Meiji's 25th wedding anniversary. 
