<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State-Owned Sector Remains Backbone of China's Economy (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- According to the State Statistics
Bureau's monthly report, which was made public here today, China's
state-owned enterprises had 84.5 billion yuan (about 10.18 billion
US dollars) in added value output last month, accounting for 47
percent of the nation's total in industrial sector and
representing a year-on-year increase of 4.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Although performance is still slack in China's state-owned
sector, a revival is hoped for and the state-owned enterprises
remain a major force in the country's economic take-off. Since the
beginning of the year, state-owned enterprises have maintained a
growth rate of 6.2 percent or more.
</P>
<P>
Qiu Xiaohua, chief economist of the SSB, says that the sector's
competitive edge was largely improved by practice in the market
economy, and a number of large state-owned enterprises which
benefited from structure readjustments are now taking the lead in
the revival.
</P>
<P>
He said that until the end of the century, the state-owned
sector will generate a third of the country's economic output, and
their assets will account for two-thirds of the country's
total. So, state-owned enterprises will still play a decisive role
in the national economy.
</P>
<P>
A number of government officials and economists share Qiu's
optimism and point out that the sector is now in better shape than
before because most large and medium-sized enterprises, the output
value and sales of which amount to 60 percent of the country's
whole, are making a profit. At least 77 percent of the enterprises
running in red are small ones.
</P>
<P>
After several years of structural reform, a good number of
state-owned giants, such as Changhong, Chunlan and Baoshan Iron
and Steel Group, have increased per capita productivity to a level
similar to that of advanced nations, and have become money makers
for local governments.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, despite the number of loss-making enterprises, which
account for 30 percent or more, sound growth was achieved in the
state-owned sector as a whole, analysts say.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State-Owned Sector Remains Backbone of China's Economy (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Structural reforms have proven an effective means of revamping
China's big enterprises and are now spreading over the country. In
Shanghai, 80 percent of the state-owned enterprises participated
in the reforms. The debt to asset ratio dropped from 80 percent to
65 percent in the state-owned sector by the end of 1996, and will
reach 60 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Chen Qingtai, deputy director of State Economic and Trade
Commission, says that in addition to structural readjustments, the
central government will quicken the pace of enterprise reform this
year, in optimizing asset mix, encouraging mergers, and using
bankruptcy to improve business.
</P>
<P>
He said that, as the country enters a new round of economic
growth, the status of state-owned enterprises will not change.
</P>
<P>
Zheng Haihang, a research fellow at the Chinese Academy of
Social Sciences, says that China's economic growth over the past
two decades has been based on the stable development of the
state-owned sector.
</P>
<P>
Even though there were serious losses in the 1991-1996 period,
state-owned enterprises generated an annual increase of 15.53
percent in added value, which was quite high for an economic
sector as a whole, said Zheng.
</P>
<P>
It is the state-owned enterprises that make up most of the
central government revenues and have borne the cost of reforms
during the past several years, Zheng said.
</P>
<P>
As long as the Chinese government sticks to an open-door reform
policy, a steadily growing state-owned sector playing a leading
role in the national economy will be the best means to maintain
social stability and balance economic development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
