<HEADLINE> Chinese General Meets Zimbabwe Army Commander </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- General Zhang Wannian, the
vice-chairman of China's Central Military Commission (CMC), in a
meeting with Zimbabwe's Army Commander C. G. Chiwenga here today,
said that China attaches importance to improving relations with
Zimbabwe and other African nations.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that bilateral cooperation in politics, the economy,
culture, and other areas has developed greatly since the two
countries established diplomatic relations, and that, "We are very
satisfied with it."
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin visited six African nations last year and
Premier Li Peng visited seven African countries last month,
bolstering Sino-African cooperative relations, he said. Generally
speaking, the international situation is becoming more relaxed,
the multi-polar pattern continues to grow, and peace and
development are now seen as two major topics in the world, he
added.
</P>
<P>
However, the world is not yet peaceful, he noted, because
hegemony and power politics still exist, and some regional
conflicts are not ending.
</P>
<P>
Zhang expressed his appreciation for Zimbabwe's adherence to
the "one China" policy and its support for China in international
affairs.
</P>
<P>
Chiwenga said that the two countries have a long-standing
friendship, and he expressed his thanks to the Chinese government
for its help, and said that no matter how the international
situation changes, the Zimbabwean people will be friends of the
Chinese people forever.
</P>
<P>
Present on the occasion were Xiong Guangkai, deputy chief of
the General Staff of the Chinese People's Liberation Army, and
Lucas Pande Tavaya, Zimbabwe's Ambassador to China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
