<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Issues Post-handover Passport Application Forms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong government began
distributing application forms for post-handover passports this
morning, with local residents queuing up at immigration offices
throughout Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Over 91,000 application forms for Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) passports were handed out up to
16:00 local time, an official with the Immigration Department told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
It was only part of the overall figure on the first day of
issue, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The new passports will be signed and issued to local residents
starting on July 3.
</P>
<P>
In Wan Chai, specially set up counters were jammed with
applicants and the Immigration Department has allocated over 200
staff to process the expected over five million applications.
</P>
<P>
Chinese citizens living abroad can go to over 200 Chinese
embassies for collecting application forms for HKSAR passports,
said the Immigration Department official.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the Basic Law, all the Chinese citizens
living in Hong Kong have the right to apply for a HKSAR
passport. Some local residents said a HKSAR passport not only
serves as an identification paper for a Chinese citizen but also
makes travel more convenient.
</P>
<P>
So far at least 27 countries have publicly announced that they
will grant visa-free access to HKSAR passport holders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
