<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: 99 Years Make A Difference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Yesterday's headlines were
business as usual at China's leading newspaper, the People's
Daily, with news centering on the country's economic successes and
foreigners' growing awareness of the powerhouse status China is
attaining.
</P>
<P>
What a difference 99 years make.
</P>
<P>
On June 9, 1898, Britain forced the then Chinese government to
sign "The Convention Respecting An Extension of The Hong Kong
Territory," under which the New Territory were leased to Britain
for 99 years.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting marking the event yesterday, historians from the
Chinese Academy of Social Sciences referred to it as "The Day of
National Humiliation."
</P>
<P>
News about the signing of the Convention was published in local
newspapers one week later. At first, no one paid much attention.
</P>
<P>
In the late 19th century, many Chinese thought of their country
as the center of the universe; only a few pioneer spirits were
awakened by the cannon fire of British warships and joined the
struggle for the country's reunification.
</P>
<P>
"Zongli Yamen," or the Foreign Ministry of the Qing Dynasty
(1644-1911), is located in a hutong, or side street, near
Tiananmen Square. Its main building was burned by Western allies
during their 1900 invasion of Beijing. Only parts of it are
preserved and are expected to be put on a relics protection list.
</P>
<P>
Yesterday, the movie "Opium War" premiered in the Chinese
capital city. The film about Britain's overtaking of Hong Kong is
the most expensive in Chinese movie-making history.
</P>
<P>
"The aim of shooting such a movie is to remind all Chinese of
the past. For any nation, ignorance of the outside world means
backwardness, and a backward country is doomed to be bullied,"
said Xie Jin, the 74-year-old director of the movie. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Offers Indonesia Su-27, Mig-29 Planes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia, along with other
southeast Asian countries, has been indirectly offered
Russian-made su-27sk and mig-29 warplanes long before it canceled
its plan to purchase nine f-16s from the United States, a Russian
diplomat here said today.
</P>
<P>
"Russia never links the selling of warplanes to political
affairs. This is our policy. We do not want to interfere in the
domestic affairs of other countries," information officer of the
Russian embassy here Louri Noskov said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas said last Friday that
Indonesia had decided to cancel its purchase of the f-16s and
forego its participation in a military training program offered by
the U.S. due to "unjustified criticism in the US Congress against
Indonesia."
</P>
<P>
Noskov did not comment on the cancellation.
</P>
<P>
He said Russia has also offered its warplanes to other Asian
countries, which he described as a good market for its products.
</P>
