<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Parliament Ratifies Treaty to Prevent Art </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian parliament today voted
to ratify a bill which will allow the government to join an
international treaty to prevent the smuggling of its art works
and ancient antiques.
</P>
<P>
The state-run Tehran Radio reported that the parliament
members approved Iran's membership in the treaty that would pave
the way for joint administrative assistance among signatories
of the treaty to monitor and prevent customs violations.
</P>
<P>
However, the number of the signatories of the treaty was not
reported.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian authorities concerned have accused European
embassies in Tehran of involvement in the illegal exportation of
items that are part of the cultural heritage of Iran. But no
embassy has so far been mentioned by name.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian Information Ministry, which spearheads the fight
against exportation of antiques, claimed last year that some 12
embassies, mostly European ones, were allegedly in connection
with the exportation of historically cultural artifacts that
exceeded millions of U.S. dollars in value. 
</P>
</TEXT>
