<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Meets Japanese Governor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing,
in a meeting with Isamu Takada, the governor of Japan's Nagasaki
Prefecture this afternoon, said he appreciates his efforts and
those of people in Nagasaki in promoting Sino-Japanese friendship
and exchanges between local governments of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
This year is the 25th anniversary of the normalization of the
diplomatic ties between China and Japan. In the past 25 years,
friendly cooperative relations between the two countries have
enjoyed great progress, Li said, and he hopes the exchanges and
cooperation between local governments can grow.
</P>
<P>
Takada said that his prefecture is determined to take the lead
in Japan's local governments in promoting Japan-China friendship.
</P>
<P>
Nagasaki will also observe the Japan-China Joint Statement and
the Treaty of Peace and Friendship, and be active in friendly
contacts and cooperation with China, he said.
</P>
<P>
Qi Huaiyuan, president of the Chinese People's Association for
Friendship with Foreign Countries, was present at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Takada was named the Ambassador of the
China-Japan friendship. He and his delegation are here as guests
of the China-Japan Friendship Association.  
</P>
