<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Project Hope: From a Small Village to Whole Country (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Zhang Shengli, a young boy
from a small village in north China's Taihang Mountain, never
expected the letter he wrote 10 years ago would lead to a
nationwide movement for aiding poor school dropouts.
</P>
<P>
The program, which over the past decade has received assistance
from hundreds of millions of people, has benefited 1.55 million
school dropouts in poor areas across the country.
</P>
<P>
In 1987, Zhang found himself unable to continue his studies at
the primary school in Taomugeda Village in north China's Hebei
Province, because his family could not afford school fees.
</P>
<P>
Eager to return to school, he wrote a letter to Che Zhizhong,
vice-chairman of Hebei's Laiyuan County Committee of the Chinese
People's Political Consultative Conference, asking for help.
</P>
<P>
Che had been a teacher in the Taihang mountainous area for 30
years, ever since his graduation from Beijing Normal University in
the 1950s. He was familiar with the situation in Zhang's village,
where the high mountains and deep valleys made it difficult for
villagers and domestic animals to get enough drinking water.
</P>
<P>
The 11 schoolchildren in the village faced the same situation
as Zhang.
</P>
<P>
Che urged his family, friends and colleagues to make donations
both in cash and in kind for the youngsters, and then reported the
story to higher authorities.
</P>
<P>
After investigating the situation in the village, the Central
Committee of the Communist Youth League of China came to the aid
of the children.
</P>
<P>
A report was also sent to the central government, explaining
the situation of Zhang Shengli and millions of other children in
poor areas around the country who cannot continue their
studies. Chinese leaders were deeply concerned by the report.
</P>
<P>
On October 30, 1989, the China Youth Development foundation was
established in Beijing, and in turn started a movement called
Project Hope the same year to help children in poor areas go to
school and at the same time improve the primary education system
in those areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Project Hope: From a Small Village to Whole Country (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The project has received donations from hundreds of millions of
people, including state leaders, celebrities, enterpreneurs,
government officials, workers and students.
</P>
<P>
Late Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping took the initiative to donate
to the project, and through the years other Party and government
officials have taken substantial action to support the effort.
</P>
<P>
In its first year, Project Hope received more than 100 million
yuan (about 12 million US dollars) from all over the country.
</P>
<P>
International organizations and overseas circles also
contributed. A "Hope primary school," the first of its kind in
China, which was sponsored by a United Nation organization, was
built in a village of Fengning county in Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
To date, the project has received 130 million yuan (15.7
million US dollars) in gifts from overseas Chinese, foreign
enterprises and foreigners.
</P>
<P>
The project has collected 980 million yuan (118 million US
dollars) over the past eight years, set up more than 3,600 Hope
primary schools and helped more than 1.5 million children.
</P>
<P>
About 60 million yuan (about 7.2 million US dollars) was
collected from Hebei Province, where the program originated, and
163 primary schools have been built there, with 68,000 children
returning to school.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Shengli, the first child to benefit from the project, has
been helped through primary and middle schools by the program's
foundations at various levels. He has already been enrolled in a
teacher's college in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
"I will return to my village to teach, and try to help my
fellow villagers out of poverty," Zhang said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Project Hope: From a Small Village to Whole Country (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China has set a national policy to popularize nine-year
compulsory education, including six years of primary school and
three years of middle school education.
</P>
<P>
Project Hope is a supplement to government-funded education,
which gives new opportunities to the poor rural areas, especially
those remote residential places inhabited by ethnic minorities,
where funds for education are limited.
</P>
<P>
The project has concentrated on eight poverty-stricken counties
in Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region, one of the country's poorest
areas, and helped 23,000 school dropouts there.
</P>
<P>
Small libraries have been established in 240 primary schools,
using donation from across the country.
</P>
<P>
China has combined Project Hope with the Spring Bud Project,
which was sponsored by the Children's Foundation of China to help
female school dropouts.
</P>
<P>
In east China's Zhejiang Province, about 80,000 people have
made financial contributions to both projects, and more than
60,000 school dropouts in the province have been aided.
</P>
<P>
The enrollment rates of girls of primary and middle school age
have been kept above 99.7 percent and 89.5 percent respectively in
the province, while the overall enrollment rate of children for
the nine-year-education plan rises steadily every year.
</P>
<P>
Project Hope has already begun its last round of nationwide
fund-raising, said Xu Yongguang, general-secretary of the China
Youth Development Foundation.
</P>
<P>
The program plans to raise 500 million yuan (about 60 million
US dollars), help 300,000 dropouts, and build 1,000 Hope primary
schools within one year, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Construction Bank of China began receiving money for the
project from all around the country on June 1. The German
Volkswagen Group has given one million yuan (about 120,000 US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Xu said that Project Hope will end by the year 2000, when China
expects to eliminate poverty and significantly reduce the number
of school dropouts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
