<HEADLINE> HK's Fund Sales Approaches 700 Million U.S. Dollars in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Gross sales of Hong Kong's
unit trust industry soared to a record high of 699.64 million
U.S. dollars in April, a report of the Hong Kong Investment Funds
Association (HKIFA) said today.
</P>
<P>
It said that the industry continued for the fourth consecutive
month to register strong inflows.
</P>
<P>
In April, net sales reached 258.01 million dollars, leaving the
 industry with an aggregate net inflows of 924.74 million dollars
for this year, the report noted.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the sales trend, Andrew Lo, chairman of the
HKIFA, said: "If one analyses the sales figures, one would notice
that the strong sales volume recorded in the past few months were
mainly related to two sectors: Hong Kong equity funds and Single
Asian countries (excluding Hong Kong and Japan) funds."
</P>
<P>
As to why both sectors had been so popular despite some
volatility in the markets in the past months, he said: "For Hong
Kong equity funds, a key reason is probably because investors are
positive on the outlook of both the China and Hong Kong economy as
 well as the local property market, especially as the investment
sentiment in the run-up to the handover has been positive."
</P>
<P>
This has been fueled by the fervor in "red-chips," which has
possibly increased investors interest in both Hong Kong funds and
the Chinese mainland's funds, Lo added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
