<HEADLINE> Iran to Offer Free AIDS Advice to Citizens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Iran has decided to offer free
consultations to citizens who worry that they might have
contracted the AIDS disease, a local report said here today.
</P>
<P>
The Persian daily Akhbar reported that the free-of-charge
service will be provided by Iran's Blood Transfusion Organization
(IBTO) in a bid to reduce the anxiety among the Iranians.
</P>
<P>
Director of the IBTO Jahangir Ahmadi said that the service was
offered to all, and no blood donation was requested in return at
the IBTO headquarters.
</P>
<P>
"It does not matter if they do not want to offer blood. The
people can take advantage of the guidance provided by the
centers established by IBTO," he said.
</P>
<P>
The health official here claimed that Iran has the lowest
number of AIDS patients in the world.
</P>
<P>
However, the number of AIDS cases are not regularly
disclosed. The latest official figure on AIDS cases in Iran is
some 260 AIDS patients in the country.
</P>
<P>
Health Minister Ali Reza Marandi was quoted by another Persian
daily Salam as saying last December that 122 of the Iranian
AIDS victims have died.
</P>
<P>
Out of the 260 AIDS patients who are living in Iran, 233 are
male and 27 are female, added the minister.
</P>
<P>
The discussion of the AIDS is usually hushed in Iran's mass
media. The government-controlled radio and TV stations rarely
touch upon the issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
