<HEADLINE> Prince: Jordan to Continue Aid to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Jordan will continue to contribute
a major part of its annual budget to support the programs for the
Palestinians living in 13 refugee camps in Jordan, Jordanian
Crown Prince Hassan said here today.
</P>
<P>
The crown prince made the remarks while addressing a conference
of the donor countries to the United Nations Relief and Work
Agency (UNRWA), which is aimed at calling on more help to the
U.N. agency to overcome its current financial difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Jordan spent 300 million U.S. dollars annually on the
Palestinian refugees, including rents for camp sites, the cost of
education for Palestinian students at government schools,
improvements of camp facilities and the provision of medical care
in government schools, Hassan said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jordan has exerted its utmost effort to create a
stable environment for the Palestinians by offering them the
same civil liberties and political freedoms that all the
Jordanians enjoy, said Hassan to the donors.
</P>
<P>
Jordan, with some one-fourth of its 4 million-strong
population as of Palestinian origins, has been a firm support of
the UNRWA and stands for the Palestinians' request to restore
their sovereignty on their own soil.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's annual expenditure for the refugees in the UNRWA camps
in the country equals to 80 percent of the agency's estimated
annual budget of 360 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Some one million Palestinians were made homeless during the
First Middle East War in 1948 when Israel annexed part of the
Palestinian land.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians then went to live in the refugee camps in
Jordan, Syria, Lebanon and the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
The UNRWA was established in 1949 to deal with the issues of
the 3.3 million Palestinian refugees in the Middle East
region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Praised for Growing Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Uganda developed its economy
despite its debt burden, a senior International Monetary Fund
(IMF) official said here yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Ulrike Wilson, Resident Representative of IMF in Uganda, told
a workshop organized by the Forum for Women Democracy (FOWODE)
that Uganda got debt burden relief.
</P>
<P>
"It was the first country to get relief at highly
concessionaire 'Naples' terms from the Paris Club. It is also the
first to get HIPC (highly indebted poor countries) debt relief,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
Despite Uganda's debts are increasing in sum, its debt ratio
is decreasing from 100 percent in 1990/1991 financial year to 56
percent in 1995/1996 financial year due to the rapid growth in
gross domestic product, she noted.
</P>
<P>
According to "the New Vision" today, the workshop was
sponsored by Friedrich Ebert Foundation and the Danish
International Development Agency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Maps out Plan for Asset Evaluation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- China will set up a unified policy
and legal system for asset evaluation before the end of this
century, a senior official said today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, during the Ninth Five-Year Plan period (1996-2000),
China will establish a unified sectoral self-discipline system, a
unified system for asset evaluation methods and standards, and a
unified research, education and training system for asset
evaluation, Zhang Youcai, Chinese Vice-Minister of Finance said at
the opening of a symposium on international appraisal standards
today.
</P>
<P>
As China develops a market economy, asset evaluation has become
an important channel for protecting the rights and interests of
asset owners and operators, said Zhang, who is also
director-general of the State Administration of State Property.
</P>
<P>
Asset evaluation is also playing an increasingly big role in
optimizing the distribution of resources and improving the
economic structure, he noted.
</P>
<P>
According to existing Chinese laws and regulations, state
assets must be appraised in economic activities such as setting up
Sino-overseas joint or cooperative ventures, asset auctions and
transfers, and enterprise mergers, bankruptcies and alliances.
</P>
<P>
The latest official statistics show that since China began to
evaluate assets in 1989, assets worth more than 2,202 billion yuan
(about 265.3 billion US dollars) in book value have been
appraised. As a result, the appreciated asset value has increased
by more than one trillion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Asset evaluation in China first started in the state sector and
in recent years it has rapidly spread to non-state enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Official record also shows that China had more than 3,300 asset
evaluation agencies by the end of last year and more than 50,000
professional appraisers.
</P>
<P>
Since the China Asset Evaluation Association was founded in
December 1993, grassroots associations have been set up in 23
provinces and municipalities.
</P>
<P>
The symposium drew hundreds of officials and experts from
related Chinese government departments, the International
Valuation Standards Committee and countries and regions including
the United States, France, Australia, Denmark and Hong Kong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
