<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The Arab Investment Company has decided to
increase its capital from 300 million U.S. dollars to 400 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made by the Riyadh-based company during a
meeting of its general assembly Sunday. The company declared that
its profits increased from 18.3 million dollars in 1995 to 27.7
million dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
The company reaped 6 million dollars in the first quarter of
1997 compared with 4.9 million dollars in the same period of the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Kuwait will provide Lebanon with 33 million
U.S. dollars in loan, with 2 percent of interest and a five-year
grace period, to finance drinking water projects in the Greater
Beirut area, a latest report of the Lebanese Eco News business
weekly said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement of the loan, the last of totally 200 million
dollars to Lebanon by Kuwait, was signed between the Kuwaiti Fund
for Economic Development and the Lebanese Council for
Reconstruction and Development.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Lyonnaise Des Eaux, French company specialized in
distribution of water and waste water collection and disposal
services, has opened a regional office in Amman which will
facilitate all its business within the region, Jordan Times
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The company, while serving more than 76 million inhabitants
in over 80 cities around the world, now aims to expand its
business in the Middle East region, said Joubrane Owayshek,
director for Regional Development in the Middle East and North
Africa of the French company.
</P>
<P>
The project, financed by several international bodies
including the World Bank, will handle the management of water
distribution, the provision of water and waste water services as
well as the rehabilitation of water treatment systems in the
Greater Amman areas.
</P>
<P>
ALGIERS -- The World Bank (WB) is to provide Algeria with
loans worth 1.89 billion U.S. dollars during the period of
1997-200l, informed sources close to the Algerian Finance
Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
The sources added that the loans would be employed to finance
18 projects in several fields, including housing, power,
infrastructure, boosting the private sector, providing water
resources to rural and mountainous areas, and education.
</P>
<P>
It was learned that Algeria's foreign debts have now reached
32 billion dollars, while its hard currency reserves amounts to
5.5 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to Algerian economists, the Algerian government will
try to accelerate its economic reform programs, open up further
to the outside world, and will make more efforts to fight
terrorism after the recent parliamentary election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
