<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Hong Kong's Oldest Business Club Aims at Close Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong will step into a new
era with good prospects after the changeover on July 1, said the
newly-appointed director of Hong Kong's leading chamber of
commerce.
</P>
<P>
"Now a smooth transition in Hong Kong is out of question, and
I'm optimistic about the future of Hong Kong," said Dr. Eden Woon,
the first director of Chinese origin sitting in the 136-year-old
Hong Kong General Chamber of Commerce (HKGCC).
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong will continue to be a good middle man between foreign
investors who want to do business with China's inland areas which
need great resources ranging from capital to expertise, according
to Woon, who just returned from the United States to assume the
post in the HKGCC.
</P>
<P>
Woon and his family left Hong Kong more than 30 decades ago to
emigrate to the United States. Before he came back, he had been
engaged in promoting trade between China's inland areas, Hong Kong
and the United States for five years.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, he said he believed that Hong Kong
would play a even bigger role of a money machine to channel
foreign investment into China's inland areas to fuel one of the
world's fastest growing economy. Currently, more than 60 percent
of overseas investment in China's inland areas comes from Hong
Kong. A sound legal system, good infrastructure facilities and
high-quality personnel sharpen the competitive edge of Hong Kong,
added Woon.
</P>
<P>
After July 1, the top priority of the chamber is to explain to
foreign investors that Hong Kong is still the best spring pad to
jump into the huge market in China's inland areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We'll tell them that Hong Kong's position as a trade and
financial hub will remain unchanged after the handover," said
Woon.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, he wanted to inject fresh blood into its
4,000-member chamber of commerce. His target is at those
China-backed companies, which are registered and operating in Hong
Kong, and which act as investment vehicles of the central and
local governments.
</P>
<P>
Now only 150 China-backed companies have joined the chamber,
which is the largest and most populous business club in Hong
Kong. At present, multinational companies account for 30 percent
of the total number of the affiliated members and local companies
make up two thirds.
</P>
<P>
Woon hoped to attract more China-backed companies, which are
emerging as one of the heavy players in Hong Kong's free economy.
</P>
<P>
As a further step, Woon wanted to strengthen ties between
members of the HKGCC and enterprises in China's inland areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
