<HEADLINE> Major Reshuffle Expected in Nigerian Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 10 (Xinhua) -- A major reorganization of Nigeria's
cabinet, the Federal Executive Council, is expected before the end of
this year, the Nigerian Tribune reported today.
</P>
<P>
At least two-thirds of the federal ministers will be appointed from
the Vision 2010 Committee, Nigeria's first ever organization launched
by the government to sketch national long-term socio-economic
development strategies.
</P>
<P>
The 197-member committee, comprising some ministers, experts from
all circles and religious leaders, is expected to submit its final
report to the head of state, General Sani Abacha by September this
year, according to the local newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Quoting government sources, the report said the new
ministers, whose identities will be made public by General Abacha in
his October 1 independence anniversary broadcast to the nation, would
be selected across the 13 sub-committee of Vision 2010.
</P>
<P>
Observers noted that this is the first public report of the
speculated reshuffle which has long been spreading among diplomatic,
business and journalist circles.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Vision 2010 Chairman Chief Ernest
Shonekan, an economist and once temporary head of state, is said to be
currently consulting with members of his committee so as to present a
credible list of the new ministers to General Abacha.
</P>
<P>
He is reported to be insisting on pure merit, instead of the usual
lobbying, to enhance high productivity. However, his conviction, based
on which the selection is to be made, is subject to ratification of the
head of state.  enditem

