<HEADLINE> Balkan Foreign Ministers Agree to Have Annual Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers participating in
the Thessaloniki conference decided Monday to establish an annual
meeting on a rotational basis.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the conclusion of the first day of the conference,
Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos announced that they had
agreed to hold their next meeting in Turkey next year, in 1999 in
Romania and in the Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia (FYROM) in
2000.
</P>
<P>
They had also decided to propose an informal meeting of Balkan
leaders to take place annually, starting with Greece at the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also agreed that such meetings should also be held
by the ministries of national defense, public order and commerce
from Balkan countries.
</P>
<P>
The proposals raised by the ministers also include a crisis
prevention and management center in Sofia, Bulgaria, and a mutual-
assistance fund for aid and development.
</P>
<P>
Pangalos said that Balkan cooperation had entered a new era.
</P>
<P>
"Up to now, there were ideas and meetings that had an uncertain
outcome. Today we succeeded in establishing Balkan cooperation as a
perspective for the future," he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Balkan people should be able to discuss
their problems on their own, "without foreign intervention."
</P>
<P>
The two-day conference of Balkan foreign ministers is to end
today with a joint statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
