<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Makes Progress in Asset Evaluation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- China has made significant
progress in asset evaluation since it was initiated eight years
ago, a senior official said today.
</P>
<P>
Chinese evaluators appraised assets worth more than 2,202
billion yuan (about 265.3 billion US dollars) in book value
between 1989 and last year. The post-evaluation value of the
appraised assets reached 3,241 billion yuan, over one trillion
yuan more than the book value.
</P>
<P>
Asset evaluation has become an inseparable part of China's
socialist market economy, Pan Yue, deputy director of the State
Administration of State Property (SASP), told a symposium on
international appraisal standards.
</P>
<P>
Through asset evaluation, the State's rights and interest as
asset owner have been safeguarded, he told the symposium, which
was co-sponsored by the China Asset Evaluation Association, the
United Nations Development Program and the China International
Center for Economic and Technological Exchanges of the Ministry of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
According to existing Chinese laws and regulations, state
assets must be appraised for economic activities such as setting
up Sino-overseas joint or cooperative ventures, asset auctions and
transfers, and enterprise mergers, bankruptcies and alliances.
</P>
<P>
Asset evaluation in China first started in the state sector and
in recent years it has rapidly spread to non-state firms. Official
statistics show that the non-state sector accounted for more than
a quarter of the combined value of assets appraised last year.
</P>
<P>
Officials and experts participating in the symposium, including
those from the United States, France, Australia, Denmark and Hong
Kong, noted that asset evaluation has become a rudimentary
instrument for China to optimize the distribution of resources and
promote economic reorganization.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, China had more than 3,300 asset
evaluation agencies and over 50,000 professional
appraisers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
