<HEADLINE> Zambian Computer Expert Hopeful About Software </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Software production could become a
major earner for Zambia if fully exploited, a Zambian computer expert
has said.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia today quoted the expert, Jeremiah Phiri, as
saying in Kitwe, northern Zambia, at the weekend that the
computer software production is a potential money spinner because
it requires very little material inputs.
</P>
<P>
"All you need is a computer and diskettes and a brain, then you can
produce your software," Phiri said.
</P>
<P>
He said the market is readily available in the country as 60
percent of companies are using computers.
</P>
<P>
At present few local companies produce software and most firms
only sold computers, he said.
</P>
<P>
People face problems because they prefer to import software, some
of which is of inferior quality, said the computer expert.
</P>
<P>
"Because the software is from developed countries, people think it
is always of high quality. Some of the software packages have been
rejected in developed countries and are just dumped in Africa where
people accept anything," Phiri said. enditem

