<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- While 14 other European Union (EU) countries agreed on Monday
that a pact of budgetary stability should be signed one week later
at the Amsterdam EU summit, France asked for a delay of the signing
of the pact. French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin wishes to add
clauses on employment and economic coordination to the text of the
pact, which is aimed at punishing those countries which have
excessive budgetary deficit after the launching of the European
single currency.
</P>
<P>
-- Attending Monday for the first time the EU finance ministers'
meeting in Luxembourg, the new French Finance Minister Dominique
Strauss-Kahn Monday played the difficult role of showing the change
of attitude of the French government over the European single
currency while not creating a crisis in Europe. He said that while
France does not call for a renegotiation of the budgetary stability
pact on European single currency, it cannot accept the present text
of the pact either and wants to discuss it again with other European
countries.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- During his first ``sortie'' to the Economic and Financial
Council of the 15 EU countries, new French Finance Minister
Dominique Strauss-Kahn made the first coup of restraint of the
Socialist government on European integration by calling for ``time
of reflexion'' on the monetary stability pact for European single
currency. This action will no doubt block the EU Amsterdam summit
to be held on June 16-17 from adopting the text of the pact.
</P>
<P>
-- Apart from the European single currency, the new French
government is expected to make public its attitudes on several other
key issues, including the raise of the guaranteed minimum wage, or
the SMIC, the reduction of the 20.6 percent added value tax, and the
dispute over the closing by the Renault automaker of the Vilvoorde
car assembly plant in Belgium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
