<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Race To New Record After Holiday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market raced
to a fresh high on its return from the long weekend, adding over
one percent today after Wall Street continued its record-breaking
run overnight.
</P>
<P>
Industrial stocks, particularly the banks, were the star
performers, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed 28.0 points, or 1.08 percent,
higher at 2628.9, topping the previous record of 2625.7 set on
June 2.
</P>
<P>
"There seemed to be two major developments today - obviously
what happened on (Wall Street) was pretty positive ... and the ANZ
job ads came out," Austock Brokers' David Perry said.
</P>
<P>
The ANZ Bank job ads series, which fell 7.3 percent in May but
was 8.6 percent higher in the three months ended May, had a
"slight positive impact", Perry said.
</P>
<P>
He said the banking sector in particular benefited from lower
bond yields and the Reserve Bank of Australia's decision to lower
the prime assets requirement for banks to three percent from six
percent.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index closed 50.5 points, or 1.24 percent,
higher at 4109.9, with the banking index 95.5 points, or 2.08
percent, stronger at 4688.8.
</P>
<P>
The all resources added 9.7 points to 1490.4.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank jumped 21 cents to 18.98 Australian
dollars, Westpac and CBA improved 29 cents to 7.46 Australian
dollars and 14.50 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index ended 4.6 points firmer at 1564.1, with gold
bullion in Sydney closed at 344.35 US dollars an ounce from 344.00
US dollars on Friday.
</P>
<P>
National turnover totaled 337.62 million shares valued at
803.01 million Australian dollars (610 million US dollars), with
rises outnumbering falls by 599 to 514. 
</P>
