<HEADLINE> Kenya to Commence Fencing Around Mt. Kenya Forest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government is
scheduled to commence an electric fence program around the Mt.
Kenya and Aberdare forests next month to reduce the conflict
between human beings and wildlife.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a three-day Partnership Stakeholders Workshop held
in Nyeri, about 160 kilometers north of Nairobi, Central
Provincial Commissioner Wilson Chepkwony said yesterday that the
program was estimated to cost over 17 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
He told the on-going workshop, which brought all mountain
region stakeholders together, that the fencing of 80 kilometers
around the Aberdare Forest had already started and the program
was expected to cover some 370 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan official was quoted by the local paper East African
Standard today as noting that the conflict between the human
beings and wildlife must be reduced at all costs because both are
important to the economy of the country.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the region around the Mt. Kenya and Aberdare
forests has the highest human/wildlife conflict in the country
arising mainly from elephants, crocodiles and hippos. 
</P>
</TEXT>
