<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Industrial Production on Steady Growth in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- China's industrial sector
maintained steady growth in May, with enterprises at the township
level or above registering an added value of 178 billion yuan, up
11.9 percent over the same month of last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the monthly report released by State Statistical
Bureau (SSB) today, the state-owned sector realized an added value
of 84.5 billion yuan, up 4.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Stimulated by the brisk domestic market, the country's light
industry generated an added value of 73.5 billion yuan, up 13.2
percent; that of heavy industry was 104.5 billion yuan, up 10.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
The sale rate of the industrial products stood at 94.99
percent, representing a year-on-year increase of 0.31 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
The SSB report said that the production of major raw materials
remained on a stable rise, with the output of pig iron, steel and
steel products going up by 10.7 percent, 6.6 percent and 11.3
percent, respectively. The increase margin in the output of ten
major non-ferrous metals stood at 13.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the country turned out an energy output of 112
million tons of standard coal, up 1.2 percent over the same month
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the growth rates of consumer goods including color
televisions, cameras, household air-conditioners and freezers
ranged 10.9 percent to 38.4 percent in output.
</P>
<P>
Textile production also reported a more rapid increase than in
previous months.
</P>
<P>
An SSB survey of 370,000 Chinese enterprises shows that the
economic benefits of industrial sector looked hopeful in the first
months of this year. During the January-April period, the
country's enterprises turned out 29.32 billion yuan in profits, up
39.2 percent over the corresponding period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the state-owned sector succeeded in making up its 1.5
billion yuan-worth loss in the first quarter, and generated
profits of 2.07 billion yuan in the period.
</P>
<P>
However, There were still a number of enterprises running in
the red. It continues to be a major problem in China's industrial
economy and the overall performance of the industrial sector is
still slack, the SSB report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA Remains Main Market for Zambia's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 10 (Xinhua)-- The Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA) has continued to be Zambia's biggest
market for its non-traditional exports (NTES), absorbing 88.2
million U.S. Dollars of its total NTES exports in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The 88.2 million Dollars represents 36.3 percent of Zambia's
total NTES valuing 242 million Dollars in 1996, according to the
latest exporter audit.
</P>
<P>
Although COMESA still accounts for Zambia's largest market,
manufacturers and other exporters are still finding it difficult
to increase exports to this market due to non-tariff and tariff
barriers.
</P>
<P>
The European Union remains Zambia's second largest market for
NTES that accounted for 73 million Dollars, representing 30.1
percent of the total NTES, with Britain being Zambia's largest
market in the EU.
</P>
<P>
The Far East accounted for 31.6 million Dollars, the third
largest export market for Zambia's NTES.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, equally emerging as crucial market with a
shorter distance, accounted for about 28.5 million Dollars of
NTES with products exported there including scrap metal, cotton,
soya beans, gemstones, tobacco, and calcium carbide.

=06101049

=06101149
NNNN
18:53 18:53 g # PAB
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
