<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sisal Production Goes Down in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Sisal output has fallen sharply
in Kenya during the last five years, according to a report from
the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Kenya produced only 27,100 tons of sisal, valued at some 15.2
million U.S. Dollars in 1996, down from 33,953 tons in 1995 and
34,220 tons in 1994, the "East Africa Standard" newspaper quoted
the report as saying today.
</P>
<P>
However, the eastern African country exported sisal worth 12.6
million Dollars last year, slightly up from 11.3 million Dollars
in the previous year, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Sisal, usually planted in arid and semi-arid areas, has
remained a major source of earning for the rural communities in
Kenya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
