<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines, Singapore to Enhance Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines and Singapore today
agreed to set up a Philippine-Singapore Action Plan to enhance
bilateral cooperation in the economic, diplomatic, cultural and
other areas.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Fidel Ramos proposed the plan in his
one-hour meeting with visiting Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok
Tong, according to a news release from the Presidential Palace.
</P>
<P>
The proposed plan will include cooperation in the areas of
information technology, education, human resource development,
science and technology and tourism.
</P>
<P>
Details of the action plan, which will serve as a blueprint for
bilateral cooperation, will be tackled by concerned Filipino and
Singaporean officials soon after Goh's three-day visit.
</P>
<P>
Both Ramos and Goh agreed to meet again next month during the
30th anniversary of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations in
Kuala Lumpur to review the progress in the formulation of the
action plan.
</P>
<P>
After their meeting, the two leaders also witnessed the signing
of a memorandum of understanding on cultural cooperation between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
At a joint press conference after the meeting, they said the
"turbulence" in Philippine-Singapore relations is "finally over"
and pledged to elevate their partnership to greater heights of
cooperation and mutual trust.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the Philippines and Singapore were strained
in March 1995 after the execution of Flor Contemplacion, a
Filipino domestic helper who was found guilty of murder by a
Singapore court.
</P>
<P>
Goh assured the Philippine public at the press conference that
Singapore will protect Filipino workers under Singapore laws and
will treat them "fairly and squarely."
</P>
<P>
Singapore is the Philippines' third largest trading partner
after the United States and Japan, getting 5.6 percent of the
country's total export.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade between the two countries surged from 803.17
million U.S. dollars in 1992 to 2.96 billion dollars last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
