<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fujian Enhances Flood Control Financially </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Southeast China's Fujian province
has developed a financial system favorable for flood prevention
and control, laying a sound foundation for enhancing resistance
against natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
Fujian is a province frequently afflicted with various natural
disasters, which greatly affect local people's normal life and
production operations, the local source said.
</P>
<P>
Lacking funds, the victims are often incapable of conducting
self-salvation.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has ordered that, starting this year,
all localities must list flood control funds within their budgets,
and no less than 500,000 yuan for prefectures (cities) and at
least 200,000 yuan for counties (districts) should be allocated.
</P>
<P>
And the flood control funds will be further expanded in the
coming years to take 3 to 5 percent of a locality's financial
revenue.
</P>
<P>
By the end of May this year, some 9 prefectures (cities) and 72
counties (districts) have worked out policies governing
administration and utilization of the flood control funds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Firmer Ahead Of Data Release </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar closed
higher today against the U.S. currency following a quiet local
session ahead of crucial local jobs data due for release on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed at 76.13 U.S. cents, from 75.95
U.S. cents on Friday. Financial markets were closed in most states
yesterday for the British queen's birthday holiday.
</P>
<P>
St George Bank Ltd senior trader Stuart Moore said the local
currency was traded today between 76.08 and 76.17 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the market was cautious ahead of the May labor
force figures from the Australian Bureau of Statistics as the data
has the potential to feed or allay fears of another cut in the
official interest rate of 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate is seen falling to 8.6 percent from 8.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed at 86.08 Japanese yen, from 87.93
on Friday and at 1.3012 Deutsche marks from 1.3148.  
</P>
</TEXT>
