<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central, Local Governments Cooperate in Sending Scholars Abroad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Cooperation between the China
Scholarship Council (CSC) and local governments has brought in
three million yuan (about 360,000 U.S. dollars) to sponsor
scholars for overseas studies or academic exchanges.
</P>
<P>
The CSC, a designated institution handling affairs related to
international studies on behalf of the State Education Commission
(SEC), has announced its first cooperation contracts with Hebei
and Liaoning provinces in sending scholars abroad.
</P>
<P>
According to the contracts that CSC signed with the two
provinces this week, CSC and the local governments will join hands
in aiding scholars abroad financially to help with local economic
and scientific advancement.
</P>
<P>
The local governments promised to pay half of a scholar's
expenses abroad, which used to be paid fully by the CSC.
</P>
<P>
Applicants from the two provinces will also have to sign a
contract with CSC and deposit a sum of honest money in an
appointed bank before they leave for abroad.
</P>
<P>
CSC sources said that such cooperation marked a new step in
China's reform on sending scholars abroad.
</P>
<P>
China started to reform its way of sending scholars abroad in
April, 1996 by making competition for international studies open
and welcoming individual applications. The reform also asks those
who go abroad at state expenses to sign an agreement with CSC,
pledging to return after completing their overseas studies.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that approximately 270,000 Chinese went
abroad for advanced training over the past 18 years. Over 120,000
of them were sponsored by the State or their work units, with the
remainder self-supporting.
</P>
<P>
Some 90,000 of these people have completed their overseas
studies and returned.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiangsu Moves to Clean Huaihe River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangsu province is
stepping up efforts to ensure that 385 enterprises in the Huaihe
River valley meet the State-set standards in industrial pollutant
discharge.
</P>
<P>
The Huaihe River valley covers an area of 66,800 sq km, with a
total population of 40 million.
</P>
<P>
Lacking efforts of environmental protection, the river water
pollution is deteriorating.
</P>
<P>
To curb deteriorating pollution, the provincial government has
worked out a program, targeting at controling the pollutant
discharge volume below the 1992 level.
</P>
<P>
To achieve the goal, the province banned and closed down 343
small enterprises with serious pollution problems last year.
</P>
<P>
To reinforce the move, the provincial government has demanded
another 385 enterprises nearby the river to meet the standards in
pollutant discharge within the prescribed time.
</P>
<P>
The province will still put in 20 million yuan this year for
the purpose of preventing and treating river pollution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
