<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FM Spokesman on Interim Report of Japanese-US Defense Cooperation Guidelines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- China hopes that Japan would,
drawing lessons from history, act with prudence and keep to the
path of peaceful development.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry Spokesman Cui Tiankai made the remark here
today at a routine press conference when asked to confirm on the
report that Japan recently sent officials to China to brief the
Chinese side on the interim report issued by Japan and the United
States on revision of the Japanese-US defence cooperation
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
Cui said the Japanese side emphasized that the rights and
obligations of Japan and the United States which were laid down in
the Japanese-US Security Treaty and some relevant agreements as
well as the basic framework of the Japan-US alliance would remain
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Japan would take all its actions within the restrictive
confines of the Japanese Constitution and in keeping with the
basic guidelines of its carrying out defence limited to its own
territory and coastal waters and observing the three nuclear-free
principles etc, and Japan and the US would take their bilateral
actions in accordance with the UN Charter and norms of
international law, Cui noted.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side reiterated its basic position and views
regarding the Japanese-US security cooperation and pointed out
that the Japan-US security alliance was a bilateral arrangement
which was formed during the Cold War times, Cui said, adding that
with the collapse of the pattern of the Cold War, such an
arrangement should especially not go beyond its bilateral
framework, in order not to arouse disquiet among neighboring
states in the Asia-Pacific region and bring about added
complication to the security situation in this region.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side also noted that due to historical reasons in
particular, the orientation of Japan's security policy was always
a matter highly sensitive to its Asian neighbors, Cui said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
