<HEADLINE> Sleeping Sickness May Re-Emerge in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Kenyans face the risk of
contracting sleeping sickness, which is said to have re-emerged
in its neighbors, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The disease is on the rise in southern Sudan, northern Uganda
and parts of the Democratic Republic of Congo (former Zaire),
Michaleen Richer, an officer with the International Medical
Corps, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"If not checked, it will soon re-emerge in the northern parts
of Kenya" as tsetse flies, which spread the disease, know no
boundaries, she warned, adding that the prevalence rate in
southern Sudan has reached 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Every year, a quarter million of the African population die
of sleeping sickness", which causes irreversible brain damage.
Most of them die mainly due to lack of early diagnosis, she said.
</P>
<P>
She called for joint efforts by the government and related
non-governmental organizations to preempt the re-emergence of the
disease.
</P>
<P>
"The control program requires an active mobile team going out
every year to screen the public so that anybody with the disease
can get treatment at the right time," she said.
</P>
<P>
Only two cases of sleeping sickness have been reported in
Kenya since December 1995. enditem

