<HEADLINE> Central China City Developing Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Zhangjiajie, a leading tourism
city in central China's Hunan Province, has been making efforts to
build basic tourist facilities and protect the environment over
the past decade.
</P>
<P>
Since Zhangjiajie City was established in 1988, more than four
billion yuan has been allocated for the construction of
transportation and telecommunications facilities, such as the
Zhangjiajie airport, highways in urban areas and scenic sites, as
well as program-controled and mobile telephone systems.
</P>
<P>
Zhangjiajie airport has launched air routes to a dozen large
and medium-sized cities including Beijing, Shanghai, and
Guangzhou. Another eight itineraries have been scheduled for
opening this year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, more than 2,000 kilometers of highways have opened
for traffic in the city. Construction on a high-grade highway from
the urban area to the scenic area will soon be completed.
</P>
<P>
While building the facilities, the city did not forget the
protection of the environment.
</P>
<P>
Zhangjiajie has issued a series of regulations to ensure the
quality of urban air and drinkable water, and control noise. More
than 20 pollutive enterprises have been shut down, and more than
20 million yuan has been invested for over 100 pollution-control
projects.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the city hosted more than 1.8 million
overseas and domestic tourists last year, with tourism earnings
reaching 450 million yuan, hitting an all-time high.  
</P>
</TEXT>
