<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest China's Ancient Caverns Becoming Popular Tourist Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The ancient caverns created
millions of years ago in Benxi of northwest China's Liaoning
Province have now become a popular tourist site.
</P>
<P>
The caverns consist of a water cavern, and a dry cave with a
length of 280 m.
</P>
<P>
The water cavern, with an area of 36,000 sq m and a
3,000-m-long underground river, is a super limestone karst cave
formed several millions of years ago.
</P>
<P>
The water flow in the cavern is two to seven meters deep,
through unique formations of stalactite and stalagmite and
surrounding walls. A wide gate of the water cavern is situated on
the bank of a local river, where archaeological findings proved
the existence of human activities some 4,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The cavern region has so far attracted more than 6.5 million
tourists from 119 countries and regions since it was developed
into a tourist site in the mid-1980s, according to local sources.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
