<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho's New Party Controls Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho Prime Minister Ntsu
Mokhehle yesterday declared a handover of government to his newly-
formed political party from the long-ruling Basutholand Congres
Party (BCP).
</P>
<P>
Mokhehle made the announcement in a statement issued in
Maseru, capital of the mountain kingdom in southern Africa,
according to local press reports.
</P>
<P>
Mokhehle said his new Lesotho Congress for Democracy (LCD) had
taken over the resigns of power from the BCP, and controlled a
majority of parliament with the support of 41 of the 64 parliament
members.
</P>
<P>
Mokhehle's cabinet ministers would all remain the same, having
made the jump to the new party along with their leader.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho Foreign Minister Albert Maope, a new member of the LCD
government, said the country's constitution allowed members of
parliament to "align themselves with any other political movement
parliament".
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the BCP, which tried to expel Mokhehle as
its leader in March, condemned the move as a "coup d'etat", adding
that the prime minister showed disrespect for the people who
elected him.
</P>
<P>
Some extra-parliament parties, including the Basutho National
Party and the National Progressive Party, also condemned the
move, which they termed unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
The two parties said they would consider protest action against the
government.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho's supreme court had ordered the BCP to elect a new leader
at its annual congress at the end of July, after several senior members
attempted unsuccessfully to oust Mokhehle earlier this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
