<HEADLINE> Israel Negotiates Billion-Dollars Of Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Israeli defense firms are
negotiating some 10.5 billion U.S.dollars worth of contracts with
foreign clients and expect more than half to be signed by the
year 2000, The Jerusalem Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
The pro-government English daily quoted Ilan Biran, Defense
Ministry director-general as saying that more than 60 percent of
the contracts are being negotiated with clients from the Far East
and Australia.
</P>
<P>
Ilan Biran said at a news conference in Tel Aviv Monday that in
1996 Israel signed contracts that totaled 2 billion dollars, and
this year, it has so far concluded more than 1 billion dollars in
contracts.
</P>
<P>
Currently the second most active area is Western Europe,
where Israeli firms are negotiating nearly 1.4 billion dollars
of contract, according to the source.
</P>
<P>
The potential lies more in Eastern Europe, where officials
expect to win contracts of 1.47 billion dollars by the year
2000. North America is expected to collect close to 700 million
dollars in defense contracts within the next two to three years.
</P>
<P>
Biran said that he hopes the Israeli defense firms will
cooperate with each other abroad and embark on joint marketing
and manufacturing ventures. This, he said, would eliminate
inefficiency and needless competitions.
</P>
<P>
Military sales are a major foreign currency earner for
Israel. The country's large defense industry has suffered much
in recent years, due to a fierce competition at the shrinking
post-cold war market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
