<HEADLINE> Israeli Politicians to Be Probed for Connection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Several Israeli cabinet
ministers and members of the Knesset (Israel's parliament)
are to be interrogated by Israeli police for their suspected
connection to a reputed Russian Mafia boss.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported today that eight leading figures from
the Likud, Labor Party and Yisrael Ba'aliya would be questioned
by police.
</P>
<P>
Zvi Ben-Ari, believed by police as one of the most powerful
and dangerous heads of the Russian Mafia, was arrested on May 12
on suspicion that he defrauded Russian banks of 85 million
U.S. dollars and was involved in the murders of two prominent
critics of the Russian Mafia.
</P>
<P>
Israeli police said that Ben-Ari, formerly known as Gregory
Lerner, immigrated to Israel in 1989, was detained, along with
five aides, at Israel's Ben-Gurion Airport while allegedly
trying to flee the country.
</P>
<P>
The radio reported that the suspicions against Ben-Ari
have widened and police now suspect he tried to "take over" one
of the three political parties to win greater legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
However, police spokeswoman Linda Menuhin would not confirm
the report, saying that "the police will call any public
figure for investigation, if it is necessary."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ben-Ari was remanded for an additional 13 days
Monday by Petah Tikva Magistrate's Court near Tel Aviv. He has
already been in jail for 30 days.
</P>
<P>
Ben-Ari, known for leading a flamboyant lifestyle in Ashkelon
in southwest Israel, was arrested in Switzerland in 1991 on the
request of Russian police on suspicion of extortion.
</P>
<P>
He was imprisoned and then released. 
</P>
</TEXT>
