<HEADLINE> Chinese Private Enterprises Employ More Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Privately-run enterprises and
individually-operated household firms in Fujian Province, east
China, have begun to join the government's effort to ease local
reemployment pressure by employing more workers laid off from
state enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-five private enterprises and more than 20 individual
households in the provincial capital city of Fuzhou held a job
fair for laid-offs on 7 June, briefing employment information for
the applicants.
</P>
<P>
Around 3,000 laid-off workers visited the fair and some of them
were hired on the spot. "My company welcomes laid-off workers,
because they have specialized skills, a good sense of professional
integrity, and cherish new job opportunities," said manager Lin of
an automobile parts factory.
</P>
<P>
Lu Weiya, owner of a bakery, hired six laid-off women workers,
as she herself had been one of them. "The important thing is you
should still have confidence when you are displaced," she said.
</P>
<P>
"We mean to tell society by this fair that private enterprises
and individual households are willing to help the State get over
the difficulty," another provate owner said.
</P>
<P>
Laid-off workers have begun to get accustomed to the
unfavorable change in looking for jobs. "I have no other choices,
and would like to do any hard job if offered fair treatment," said
a laid-off worker. 
</P>
