<HEADLINE> Guizhou Attracts Overseas Funds for Road Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Transfer of road management rights
will soon become a widely accepted way of fund-raising in
southwestern Guizhou province, which is actively pooling money to
fulfil aits road building plans.
</P>
<P>
In its first try at pooling, the province earned nearly 300
million yuan from selling 30 percent of the management rights of
two high-grade roads to a Hong Kong bank.
</P>
<P>
"All the funds raised from the management rights transfer will
be put into new road building projects, and this makes it an
effective way of capital raising and will surely expedite
Guizhou's road construction greatly," said Lu Wanli, director of
the Provincial Communications Administration.
</P>
<P>
Guizhou is a mountainous province, and as much as 87 percent of
the province's transportation depends on the highways. However,
capital shortage remains a problem, since at least ten billion
yuan is needed to complete its road-building goals during the
Ninth Five Year Plan (1996--2000).
</P>
<P>
The province has opened its arms to overseas capital inflow in
a variety of ways, including BOT (Build-Operate-Transfer),
management rights transfer and overseas government loans. In its
regulations on overseas investment last year, the province grants
preferential treatments to foreign investors interested in
Guizhou's infrastructures.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investors have since shown increasing interest in the
province's road building projects and held negotiations on
cooperation with the province's communications authorities.
</P>
</TEXT>
