<HEADLINE> China to Ensure Power Supply for Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- By the year 2000, the average
annual power outage will be less than one hour for all big or
mid-sized Chinese cities, according to Lu Yanchang, vice minister
of the Power Industry.
</P>
<P>
The reliability rate of the power supply for major Chinese
cities has reached 99.3 percent, and is expected to hit 99.9
percent by the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
Currently the major reason for China's unsustainable power
supply is the scarcity of power resources, which cannot meet the
fast-growing demand. The situation especially aggravates during peak
seasons of electricity use.
</P>
<P>
Also contributing to the problem are the regular check-ups and
poor management of the electricity network.
</P>
<P>
As many as 238 Chinese cities reported their average power
outage period had been shortened by 16.55 hours in 1995, marking a
great improvement in the power-supply situation, statistics from
the Ministry of Power Industry show. 
</P>
</TEXT>
