<HEADLINE> Chongqing to Become Telecom Hub in Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The telecom authorities in
Chongqing, China's fourth municipality after Beijing, Shanghai and
Tianjin, have mapped out a plan to speed up telecom construction
and turn the city into a telecommunications hub in southwest China.
</P>
<P>
"Chongqing has set the goal to build advanced, efficient and
safe telecom networks so as to meet the rapid social and economic
development in the city," said He Tingchang, director of the
Chongqing Telecommunication Administration.
</P>
<P>
According to He, by the year 2000, every 100 people in the
whole city share eight telephone sets while in the city proper 100
people have 52 sets. The number of mobile phone users is to
increase from the current 80,000 to 400,000 in 2000.
</P>
<P>
He believes this goal is attainable, as previous work in the
area has laid a solid foundation for future development.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing is now the key node of two state optical cables
linking southwest China with the country's central region.
</P>
<P>
Also, the city has opened direct telephone service with more
than 700 domestic cities and 180 countries and regions
worldwide. Its mobile telecom network has hooked up with China's
national nets.
</P>
<P>
However, he also admitted that in a city which now has a
population of 32 million, his department had difficulties
modernizing its telecom sector, particularly in its vast rural
areas. 
</P>
