<HEADLINE> Inflation Drops in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Inflation in Kenya declined to
2.4 percent last month from 4.0 and 2.8 percent in March and
April, the Daily Nation newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank Monthly Economic Review for this month said
the underlying month-on-month inflation also fell to 6.9 percent
in May from 7.3 percent in March in the eastern African country.
</P>
<P>
The underlying average annual inflation declined to 8.8
percent in May from 9.0 percent in March.
</P>
<P>
The continued decline in inflation that started in January has
been attributed to the monetary and fiscal policies that have
significantly slowed down the expansion of the money supply, said
the review.
</P>
<P>
The slowdown in money supply expansion is partly due to
reduced government borrowing from the central bank, which fell to
3.7 million U.S. Dollars compared with 339 million Dollars during
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
This has eased the inflationary pressures that stem from
excess demand, said the review.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the strengthening of the Shilling exchange rate
throughout 1996 and early 1997 has helped reduce prices of the
imported inputs, said the report. enditem

