<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Cabinet Reshuffle Strengthens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President Chandrika
Kumaratunga effected a cabinet reshuffle yesterday, making a
series of changes in the cabinet and increasing the number of
cabinet members from 23 to 30 in an effort to strengthen her
position.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts here see these changes as a move by
Kumaratunga to strengthen the position of herself and that of the
main coalition partner, the Sri Lanka Freedom Party (SLFP), in her
Peoples' Alliance government by giving key portfolios to her
loyalists and loyalists of the SLFP. They also believe that it is
a move to clean up the government and close its ranks.
</P>
<P>
This may also be a forerunner to a possible snap election later
this year in the event of her political package, namely the
government's devolution proposals, being unable to obtain the
required two-thirds majority in the parliament. Loyalists in key
positions will be helpful in such an eventuality.
</P>
<P>
In bringing about these changes, Kumaratunga dismissed from the
cabinet the leader of another coalition partner, the New
Democratic United National Lalith Front (NDUNLF), Srimani
Athulathmudali, who held the portfolios of transport, environment
and women's affairs.
</P>
<P>
Athulathmudali refused to agree to her party contesting last
April's local government elections under the People's Alliance
banner and instead put up the Independent Groups, owing to
political views different from those of the president.
</P>
<P>
In a statement on the cabinet reshuffle, Athulathmudali accused
the People's Alliance of breaking another election pledge by
stripping her of her cabinet post. It violates the terms of an
agreement entered into by her party and the Peoples Alliance, she
charged.
</P>
<P>
She claimed that despite several constraints, she discharged
her duties as a minister with utmost responsibility. She added
that obstacles such as this does not block her party, instead they
will serve as a stepping stone to the future.
</P>
<P>
Among the surprise changes made by Kumaratunga was the removal
of the popular Dharmasiri Senanayake, the SLFP party secretary,
from the media portfolio. Senanayake however retains his post as
the aviation and tourism minister. He had proposed legislation to
set up a broadcasting authority which the Supreme Court ruled
against a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
Posts and Telecommunications Minister Mangala Samaraweera, a
close associate of the president, has obtained the additional
media portfolio.
</P>
<P>
Kumaratunga has also divested herself of some of the portfolios
she held. She keeps only the defense, finance and planning
portfolios and has given that of Buddha Sasana to Cultural and
Religious Affairs Minister Lakshman Jayakody. The portfolio of
plan implementation has gone to new entrant Jeyaraj Fernandopulle
while that of ethnic affairs and national integration was given to
Justice and Constitutional Affairs Minister G. L. Peiris.
</P>
<P>
Besides, 10 of the 11 new deputy ministers appointed by
Kumaratunga in the reshuffle are members of the SLFP Mulberry
Group (backbenchers), which has been fighting against particularly
waste, corruption and other illegal activities involving ruling
party members. And They are Kumaratunga's strong supporters,
according to political sources here.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
