<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 07:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu: Har Homa Settlement Building to Continue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu has stressed that the construction of Jewish
settlement at Har Homa (or Jabal Abu Ghoneim) in Jerusalem, as
well as in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, would continue.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made the remarks late Monday night at a meeting of
the Knesset (Israel's parliament) members of the hardline
Likud-Gesher-Tsomet coalition. He categorically rejected reports
that any sort of promise had been made to halt the settlement
building.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Israeli media reported that the Israeli
and Palestinian negotiating teams, along with Egyptian
mediators, were trying to resolve the problem of the settlement
construction in Jerusalem through Israeli agreement to "slow
down" the construction at Har Homa to a near halt.
</P>
<P>
"We are now in the midst of a negotiating process in which we
first must make sure that the Palestinian side lives up to its
commitments to combat terror and to cease murdering land dealers
and other innocent people," the Israeli premier said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that Sunday's negotiations between Israel and
the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) in the Egyptian capital
of Cairo did not result in any understanding about renewing the
process.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks between the two sides stalled again in March
after Israel started building a controversial new Jewish
neighborhood at Har Homa in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The PNA said that Israel must stop the construction before
talks can resume, while the Jewish state insisted that the PNA
crack down on terror and reestablish full security cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Through Egypt's mediation, Israel and the PNA resumed contact
by holding a meeting in Cairo Sunday; however, no progress was
made in renewing the peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"But we are meeting again on Thursday," Netanyahu said. "For
my part, I still would like to see the Palestinian side live up
to its bargain and then I would like to enter a speeded up
negotiation for the final status agreement."
</P>
<P>
His guidelines for that agreement, Netanyahu said, will "take
into account the reality and conditions already created on
ground, but we will strive to maintain in Israeli hands the most
vital national assets."
</P>
<P>
Among the guidelines for a final status deal, Netanyahu
listed "fortifying the Jordan River as our eastern boundary and
enhancing Israel's direct control over the Jordan Valley and the
mountain ranges which control it."
</P>
<P>
He added that "it should be self-evident that we should have
absolute responsibility and exclusive sovereignty in greater
Jerusalem."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu again emphasized his objection to the establishment
of a Palestinian state in the Palestinian autonomous areas,
saying "such a state means an Arab army which would threaten
Israel's very existence." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
