<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pacific Economic Outlook Published </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The annual GDP growth rate in the
Pacific region is predicted to stand at 4.1 percent, according to
the recently-published report "Pacific Economic Outlook 1997-1998."
</P>
<P>
The region's GDP rate for 1997 and 1998 will be 5.5 and 5.7
percent, respectively, excluding that for the United States and
Japan, said the report, which was compiled by the Pacific Economic
Outlook of the Pacific Economic Cooperation Council (PECC).
</P>
<P>
The report noted that the growth rate of the consumer product
index for the two years will be 3.9 and 3.5 percent in the region,
lower than 8.6 percent in 1995 and 4.1 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the low inflation rate to the drastic
drop in the inflation rate in Russia and the Mexico, and the
continued high economic growth and low inflation rate in China and
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
The PECC gives regular seminars annually, and bases its annual
report on economic forecasts of the participants.  
</P>
</TEXT>
