<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Per-capital Income in Northeast China Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Per-capita income of urban
residents in northeast China's Liaoning province reached 4,210
yuan last year, according to a recent survey.
</P>
<P>
The survey finds that the population in this major industrial
province accounts for half of its four million people. Per-capita
income last year was up 13.3 percent from the previous year, and
was up 4.7 percent when adjusted for inflation.
</P>
<P>
The study was conducted by the province's urban social and
economic investigation team. A random sampling was made among
3,350 households in the province's cities and towns.
</P>
<P>
Households with an annual income of less than 3,000 yuan were
down from 46.7 percent to 36.1 percent of the total last year,
while those with more than 3,000 yuan annually were up 10.6
percentage points from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The research result shows that more money is being spent on
phone bills, entertainment, and health care rather than on basic
necessities like food and clothing, according to the study.
</P>
</TEXT>
