<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmer-Turned-Graduate Student Pursues New Life (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Among graduate students enrolled
in the Chinese Department of Hangzhou University last year,
32-year-old Wu Guofu stands out.
</P>
<P>
In addition to being older than most of his classmates, his
bronzed skin and callused hands reveal his past occupation as a
farmer.
</P>
<P>
Wu, now working toward his graduate degree in Chinese Ancient
Literature, lived six months ago in a small mountain village in
Jiangxi province, spending his days plowing and weeding. He
dropped out of high school at the age of 18 to help support his
family.
</P>
<P>
"At that time I was very interested in literature and hoped to
be a writer one day," he said. "I was not reconciled to being
only a farmer, I wanted to work to fulfill my dream."
</P>
<P>
During the day, he turned his attention to the rigors of
farm work. At night, he cultivated his education.
</P>
<P>
Wu had limited access to books. For months, he saved money for
a book on ancient Chinese literature, then walked a long distance
to buy it.
</P>
<P>
After his enrollment in Hangzhou University, he spent more than
1,000 yuan (120 US dollars) for books, an almost unimaginable sum
for a village farmer.
</P>
<P>
To have sufficient materials, Wu made copies of textbooks. Over
the past two years, he has transcribed more than 1 million Chinese
characters.
</P>
<P>
The road to knowledge was rough, and Wu was ridiculed by his
neighbors, who considered farm work the only respectable
profession. A grocery he opened with his wife to help support his
family added even greater responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
In spite of obstacles, Wu passed the national examination for
students pursuing an independent course of study, and later the
graduate school entrance exam.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmer-Turned-Graduate Student Pursues New Life  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Six years later, Wu was listed as one of the 46,000 students
enrolled by graduate schools across the country in 1996. That year
alone, 244,000 students in China took the graduate school entrance
test.
</P>
<P>
Wu became the first farmer to be enrolled by a graduate school
in his province, and perhaps in the entire country, according to
university authorities.
</P>
<P>
He now spends most of his time in the library or reading in his
dormitory room. Sometimes, he goes to the cinema, a favorite
spare-time activity.
</P>
<P>
So far in his graduate career, he has written five papers, one
of which soon will be published in a scholarly journal.
</P>
<P>
Called "Elder Brother" by his young roommates, Wu shares his
life experience with them, offering advice on how to get along in
society.
</P>
<P>
Wu has a great liking for his chosen field of study, but knows
there isn't much money in it. No matter what he does in the
future, he says, he will not abandon his goal to be a scholar.
</P>
<P>
Every month, he receives many letters from all over the
country, from other farmers hoping to pursue a new life through
education. Their words show their admiration for Wu.
</P>
<P>
Wu answers nearly every letter, dispensing advice when
asked. And in an article in "Today's Youth" magazine, he suggests
that others like him should carefully plan out their lives
according to their own circumstances, and make full use of their
own advantages.
</P>
<P>
"Entering graduate school is not the only way to pursue a new
life," he wrote. "What's important is to have your own dream and
never give it up." 
</P>
</TEXT>
