<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yangtze River Valley Produces One-fourth of World's Rape Seeds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Yangtze River Valley has become
the world's largest rape growing belt.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, more than 5.7 million ha of rape were planted in the
area, producing over 7.8 million tons of rape seed last year --
more than one-fourth of the world's total.
</P>
<P>
In addition to favorable soil and climate conditions, strong
science research programs have helped the area to become a rape
producer, according to Dr. Wang Hanzhong, a researcher of the
Oil-bearing Plants Institute (OPI) under the Chinese Academy of
Agricultural Science.
</P>
<P>
An oil-bearing plant research system centering around Wuhan,
the capital of central China's Hubei Province, has taken shape, he
said.
</P>
<P>
In the early 1990s, OPI raised the per ha output from 750 kg to
1500 kg with a new species known as "Zhongyou 821." The seed
strain is now planted at an annual rate of 200 ha nationwide and
has become one of the most popularly-raised varieties of the seed
in China.
</P>
<P>
There is still great potential for the expansion of the rape
growing area in the river basin, Dr. Wang said, adding that is
because there is approximately 6.7 million ha of idle farmland
there in winter, about half of which could be used for growing
rape, and the production level in the region is quite unbalanced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Marital Bliss Permeates Families in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 10 (Xinhua) -- A survey has shown that marital
status in Shanghai is holding steady, despite what many believe to
be eroding moral standards brought about by the tremendous changes
in China's economy.
</P>
<P>
Some 97 percent of the respondents said that they get along
well with their spouse, and no husband and wife said their family
life is not good.
</P>
<P>
The survey was conducted by two social sciences researchers in
the Pudong New Area, Shanghai's most rapidly-developing economic
zone. Some 1,000 families responded the questionnaires.
</P>
<P>
"Although there exist income and educational disparities, they are
no doubt affectionate couples," said Hu Shenshang, one of the
researchers, in reference to the survey respondents.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai resident Lu said, "The tip to get along with my wife
is to give up some of my hobbies to suit her tastes, and share my
time with her. And vice versa."
</P>
<P>
The survey also shows that most Shanghai men want a virtuous
and honest wife who is tender and has homemaking skills, while
most women wish their husbands to be honest and good
providers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
