<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Have Highest Number of Senior Citizens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia will have the highest
number of senior citizens in the world by the year 2025, when more
than 20 million of the nation's people will be aged 60 or above, a
population analyst said.
</P>
<P>
The projected figure marks a 414 percent increase in the number
of senior citizens since 1990, Professor Boedi Darmojo, who is
from Diponegoro University's School of Medicine in Semarang,
Central Java, said Monday, according to reports reaching here
today.
</P>
<P>
the percentage is relatively high compared to other nations, he
added, citing that Kenya's senior citizen number will increase by
347 percent, Brazil by 255 percent, India by 242 percent, China by
220 percent, Japan by 129 percent, Germany by 66 percent and
Sweden by 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
Darmojo said Indonesia will rank fifth or sixth in the world in
the number of senior citizens by the year 2020, but should be at
number one by 2025.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia is the world's fourth most populous country and its
aging population will cause an increase in spending on health
care, which many elderly people may not be able to afford.
</P>
<P>
Quoting the results of a recent study, Darmojo said 71.2
percent of Indonesia's senior citizens, most of whom are women
living in rural areas, have no formal education. Most of them are
unskilled workers, he said, adding that only 21.2 percent of male
senior citizens and 7.5 percent female senior citizens are
professionals.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, President Soeharto has said various programs must be
established to solve the many problems faced by Indonesia's senior
citizens.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at Sunday's celebration of senior citizen day, the
president said national development has successfully reduced the
infant mortality rate and improved life expectancy in the country.
</P>
<P>
Life expectancy increased to 61.3 years in 1992, from 45.7
years in 1968. At the end of the sixth five-year development plan
in 1999, life expectancy will rise to 65, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
