<HEADLINE> Chopper Lands in Bangladesh due to Bad Weather: Delhi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government Monday
formally informed Dhaka, "An Indian helicopter strayed from its
planned route due to bad weather on May 20 and was compelled to
force-land in Bangladesh territory," said an official handout.
</P>
<P>
The handout did not mention whether Delhi has expressed regret
to this incident.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi government Sunday lodged a protest with India
against the intrusion and violation of Bangladesh air space by an
Indian Air Force helicopter on May 20.
</P>
<P>
Dhaka said that an Indian helicopter landed at Chunarghat in
Habiganj district on May 20, at 1815 hours (local time). The
helicopter carried six persons in uniform and one in civilian
clothes.
</P>
<P>
"After they were told by the local people that the place they
had landed was inside Bangladesh, the helicopter took off at 1820
hours (local time) and flew eastward towards India," said the
Bangladeshi Foreign Ministry in a press release.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, Bangladesh opposition leader Khaleda Zia, who
has been accusing the government of selling out sovereignty to
India, expressed concern over the landing of the Indian
helicopter.
</P>
<P>
"It is unholy and dangerous exercise that a foreign fighter
could safely intrude into our airspace, safely landed, stayed and
took off without obstruction," said the former prime minister.
</P>
</TEXT>
