<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Calls for Re-writing of Single Currency Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 9 (Xinhua) -- France is seeking to redraw the
single-currency Stability Pact which commits European Union
countries wishing to adopt the euro on January 1, 1999, to rigorous
budgetary and financial discipline.
</P>
<P>
The pact is due to be adopted at a summit of EU leaders in
Amsterdam next week. But at a meeting of EU finance ministers in
Luxembourg, France's Finance Minister Dominique Strauss-Kahn
voiced the concerns of the country's new Socialist-led government
about the document.
</P>
<P>
He said a new chapter should be added to the pact, committing
countries adopting the euro to much closer coordination of
economic policy, focussing on growth and job creation, to offset
the potential deflationary impact of the financial constraints in
the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Strauss-Kahn called for a "period of reflection" before EU
countries adopt the accord. But he said France would stick to the
timetable and conditions for the launch of the single currency.
</P>
<P>
France's request to redraw the Stability Pact came in the wake
of the formation of the new Socialist-led government last week
following the general election.
</P>
<P>
The Socialists pledged not to impose unpopular tax increases
and spending cuts considered essential for France to cut its
budget deficit to the level required for joining the euro.
</P>
<P>
New Prime Minister Lionel Jospin is insisting on a more
flexible interpretation of the strict economic criteria set by the
Maastricht Treaty for EU countries joining the single currency.
</P>
<P>
But Strauss-Kahn denied that the request for economic
coordination was made to challenge the independence of the future
European central bank that will conduct monetary policy in the euro
zone.
</P>
<P>
He said France too saw budgetary discipline as necessary.
</P>
<P>
Even so, France's request has cast doubt on whether the
painfully-negotiated pact can be approved as scheduled next week
in Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
Gerrit Zalm, Finance Minister of the Netherlands which currently
holds the EU presidency, said today that EU members would try
hard to find solutions to the problems thrown up by France's requests
before the Amsterdam summit on June 16-17. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
