<HEADLINE> UN Investigative Team to Travel to Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 9 (Xinhua) -- A UN investigative team is
expected to travel to the Democratic Republic of the Congo later
this month to probe allegations of gross violations of human
rights in the country, a UN spokesman announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman Fred Eckhard said that US ambassador Bill Richardson
had reported to UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan that Congo
President Laurent Kabila had agreed to allow the investigative
team into Congo in two stages last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Also on Saturday, Annan requested the office of the UN High
Commissioner for Human Rights in Geneva to begin preparations for
the team's visit. Ralf Zacklin, the officer in charge of the
higher commissioner/center for human rights, said on Monday that
he had already met with senior staff to begin preparations for
sending the advance team, which is expected to enter the country
on June 20 and the full team on July 7, according to the
spokesman.  
</P>
