<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong to Remain Stable, Prosperous: Malaysian NA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong will remain stable
and prosperous after its return to China on July 1, 1997, said
Malaysian National Assembly Deputy Speaker Ong Tee Keat.
</P>
<P>
Ong said this in a recent exclusive interview with Xinhua here.
</P>
<P>
He spoke highly of the "one country, two systems" concept put
forth by the late Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping, saying it was an
"epoch-making" masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
He said the concept provided the Hong Kong people with
confidence and he believed that it would be fully implemented in
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Ong criticized the arguments by some Western media and some
western governments that Hong Kong as a world financial and
shipping center would collapse overnight after its return to
China.
</P>
<P>
The Deputy Speaker, who is also a member of the Presidential
Council of the Malaysian Chinese Association, said the western
arguments did not "hold water as they were ill-grounded."
</P>
<P>
"In my opinion, after its return to China, Hong Kong will
maintain its prosperity with the assistance of the inland areas of
China," he said.
</P>
<P>
For Hong Kong's future administration, Ong said "it must be
entirely based on the Basic law."
</P>
<P>
On the significance of the resumption of the exercise of
sovereignty over Hong Kong by the People's Republic of China, Ong
said what was most important was that the Chinese nation could be
able to wipe out the humiliation it was subjected to over the past
100 years and more.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the people of Hong Kong and the inland areas
would make efforts in the future to narrow differences in the form
of value and living style created under the different systems.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
