<HEADLINE> Foreign Purchases of US Firms Up Sharply in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Foreign spending to buy U.S.
companies increased to a record 80.5 billion dollars last year, 41
percent more than that in 1995, U.S. Commerce Department reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that most of the outlays represented
spending to acquire existing companies, 90 percent of the total
compared to 10 percent to establish new firms.
</P>
<P>
The number of individual purchases that totaled more than 1
billion dollars more than doubled to 19, compared to nine in 1995.
The very largest investments -- those over 2 billion dollars --
increased to eight from five the previous year.
</P>
<P>
British spending on U.S. companies totaled 15.5 billion
dollars, the largest amount for any nation, followed by 13 billion
in German investments and 10.2 billion in Canadian investments.
</P>
<P>
Japanese investments in the U.S. increased to 9.3 billion in
1996, up sharply from 3.6 billion in 1995. But the level was still
less than half of the peak of 19.9 billion set in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investments in service industries more than doubled to
15.3 billion dollars last year, compared to 5.9 billion the
previous year. Finance, insurance, communication and business
service companies were the most in demand.
</P>
<P>
Investments in manufacturing companies totaled 29 billion
dollars, an increase of 8.8 percent from 1995 with purchases
concentrated in industries featuring advanced technologies.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment in the United States to acquire or establish
companies was 57.2 billion dollars in 1995. The investment has
been climbing sharply for the past four years after hitting a low
of 15.3 billion in 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
