<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentina Shows Signs of Economic Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Positive signs of a recovery
of Argentina's economy, which has been in a recession since
Mexico's economic crisis of 1994, have emerged since the beginning
of this year.
</P>
<P>
The Economy Ministry said that Argentina's gross domestic
product (GDP) increased 8.1 percent during the first quarter of
this year compared with the same period in 1996 and this was the
fourth quarter in a row to show increase in the GDP.
</P>
<P>
The agricultural, manufacturing and construction sectors showed
the biggest increases between January and March.
</P>
<P>
During the first four months, the output of Argentina's
industrial sector increased 7.8 percent over the same period last
year, spurred by the increase in consumption in the automobile,
food and construction sectors, in particular.
</P>
<P>
The production of automobiles increased 43.7 percent in April
compared with the same month last year. During this period,
exports increased 111 percent and domestic sales rose 12.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
As for the consumer price index (CPI), Argentina reported three
consecutive months of deflation, -0.5 percent in March, -0.3
percent in April and -0.1 in May.
</P>
<P>
This has been a great accomplishment for the administration of
President Carlos Menem as inflation has been contained since the
beginning of 1991, with the start of the Convertibility Program
(one peso equals one U.S. dollars), which has contributed to the
economic stability in this country.
</P>
<P>
In the tax arena, tax collections reached the unprecedented sum
of 4.614 billion dollars in May, an increase of 28.6 percent over
May 1996.
</P>
<P>
In the financial circles, liquid international reserves reached
the record sum of 19.25 billion dollars compared with the sum of
15.173 billion dollars for last May, an increase of 27 percent.
</P>
<P>
Bank deposits reached the historical figure of 60.466 billion
dollars in May, an increase of 28 percent with deposits rising by
nearly seven billion dollars during the first five months of this
year.
</P>
<P>
During the first five months of this year peso deposits climbed
more than 16 percent versus 7.4 percent increases in dollar
deposits. Of the total deposits, 49.2 percent were made in pesos
and 50.8 percent in dollars.
</P>
<P>
As for foreign trade, thanks to the good performance of the
Southern Common Market, Argentina has increased its exports and
imports.
</P>
<P>
During the first 4-month period in 1997, Argentina's foreign
trade reached the unprecedented level of 16.895 billion dollars,
an increase of 25 percent over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Due to the increasingly better climate for investments, foreign
capitals increased 28 percent during the first quarter compared
with the previous year and it is expected that they will grow
another 10 billion dollars over the next four years.
</P>
<P>
According to experts, Argentina's economy has shaken off its
lethargy and is expected to grow six percent this year in face of
the recovery that is appearing along all its fronts, even though
an elevated fiscal deficit persists.
</P>
<P>
The government still faces a number of economic as well as
social problems.
</P>
<P>
The high rate of unemployment, of nearly 17 percent, is a
headache for the government in spite of its efforts to stimulate
the creation of jobs.
</P>
<P>
The delays in paying salaries, pensions and retirement funds as
well as the high unemployment levels have aggravated social
discontent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
