<HEADLINE> Indonesia Considers Buying Jets From Other Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian authorities are
considering buying fighter jets from countries other than the
United States, a military leader said.
</P>
<P>
"We are thinking of purchasing warplanes from other countries,"
Armed Forces Chief Gen. Feisal Tanjung said in Cilangkap, East
Jakarta, Monday, according to military sources here today.
</P>
<P>
The remarks came after the Indonesian government announced last
Friday that it had decided to cancel its plan to purchase nine
F-16s from the United States in reaction to U.S. Congress critics
who linked the purchase to the human rights situation in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Washington offered Indonesia 28 F-16 fighter jets that were
initially built for Pakistan in 1995. Jakarta was only interested
in buying nine and sought soft loans for their purchase.
</P>
<P>
The government's decision to cancel the F-16 deal and also
withdraw the country from a U.S. military training program has
received strong support from local observers and politicians who
see it as a snub against superpower encroachment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
