<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungary, Czech Republic Discuss NATO Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Hungarian and Czech Republic
foreign ministers held talks today over their membership bids for
NATO and the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Both countries hope to be in the first wave of countries
invited to join the North Atlantic Treaty Organization as it
expands eastward through Europe.
</P>
<P>
Laszlo Kovacs, the Hungarian foreign minister, told a joint
press conference here following his talks with his Czech
counterpart, Josef Zieleniec, it was possible both countries would
become new members of the two organizations.
</P>
<P>
He said that though NATO and Russia signed an agreement last
month setting out their new relationship in the context of the
military alliance's expansion plans, new NATO members would not be
reduced to second class status and would enjoy the same safety
guarantee as existing members.
</P>
<P>
Kovacos said that Slovakia's participation in the first wave of
NATO expansion and in the EU was also in the interests of Hungary
and the Czech Republic and would promote regional stability.
</P>
