<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Shows Beijingers Respect Teachers Most </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- A recent survey shows that
residents in the Chinese capital think that teachers, scientists
and medical doctors belong to the three most highly-respected
professions in the city.
</P>
<P>
The survey, which took four months to complete, is the first
of its kind conducted in Beijing. Respondents selected their
favorite jobs from a list of 14.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, 45.85 percent of those questioned
answered that they respect teachers most, followed by scientists
(43.65 percent), doctors (43.45 percent), engineers and
technicians, lawyers, and star athletes.
</P>
<P>
Art performers, people who are self-employed, and owners of
private businesses are among those on the bottom of the list.
</P>
<P>
With more and more Chinese realizing the importance of
education, teachers are regarded by many as the carriers of the
torch of civilization and have won widespread respect.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, a string of scandals among well-known pop singers
and movie stars, ranging from tax evasion to indiscreet behavior
in their personal lives, has dimmed their glow of fame.
</P>
<P>
Self-employed people, especially owners of private businesses,
take much of the blame when ordinary Chinese complain about
low-quality products and poor social responsibility.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Bill for Imported Crude Oil Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's bill for imported crude
and oil products jumped by 24.7 percent in the first four months
of this year over a year earlier, according to the Thai Commerce
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The country paid 56.062 billion baht (about 2.24 billion U.S.
dollars) for supplies to meet most of its energy needs. The oil
import volume rose by 8.1 percent to an average of 798,060 barrels
per day.
</P>
<P>
The bills for crude oil imports rose by 63.6 percent on those
for the same period of last year to 51.077 billion baht (2.04
billion dollars). The country paid 4.985 billion baht (199 million
dollars) for imports of refined oil products, a drop of 64
percent.
</P>
<P>
In volume terms, crude imports soared by 38.3 percent to
739,220 barrels per day while imports of finished oil products
plunged by 70.1 percent to 60,790 barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
The shift in balance between crude and refined products in the
period was due to the extra crude intake capacity offered by the
country's two new oil refineries -- Star Petroleum Refining Co.
and Prayong Refinery Co. -- in Rayong Province, eastern Thailand.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
