<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heart Disease Found to Be Top Killer of Bangkokians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Heart disease, accidents and
cancer are the top three killers of Bangkokians inflicted with
non-communicable diseases in recent years, according to
statistics.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that deaths attributable to heart disease have
increased from 262 six years ago to 418 last year while the number
of people who died in accidents jumped from 175 to 522.
</P>
<P>
Statistics for the incidence of cancer cover only three years,
showing an increase from 129 in 1994 to 164 last year.
</P>
<P>
A total of 87,225 accident victims were admitted to the seven
city hospitals in 1995, but the number went up to 88,639 last
year.
</P>
<P>
The number of people suffering from heart and cardiovascular
diseases was 62,785 last year, compared with 60,141 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The three main factors causing an rise in heart disease were
diet, pollution and living in an environment where other diseases
were present, according to the statistics quoted by the local
press today.
</P>
<P>
Most people who died of cancer suffered from lung cancer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sees Huge Personal Computer Market This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Cross sales of personal computers
in China are likely to hit 3 million units this year, today's
China Daily cited a senior engineer of the Ministry of Electronics
Industry as saying.
</P>
<P>
During the first four months of this year, Chinese PC companies
sold 215,000 units, up 126 percent over a year ago.
</P>
<P>
"Such a situation hinted at a rosy picture of the year's
computer market," he said.
</P>
<P>
Legend Group, a major personal computer supplier in China, sold
103,336 units during the first four months, an increase of more
than 140 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Chinese PC companies usually take 40 percent to 50 percent of
the domestic market share," Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
As a result, sales of PCs in the first four months would be at
least 430,000 units.
</P>
<P>
A review of market history indicates the first six months are
usually the off season for PC sales and the past six months the
peak period.
</P>
<P>
"Sales of PCs are expected to surpass the previously predicted
250,000 units for the whole of 1997," Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
Personal computers of the 586-class, based mainly on Pentium
and AMD (Advanced Micro Devices) chips, led the PC market in the
first four months, he said.
</P>
<P>
The average price of a PC is mow about 10,000 yuan (1,205 US
dollars) on the Chinese market. And it may continue to drop as
competition between Chinese and foreign PC makers becomes even
fiercer this year, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
With a higher standard of living, a growing number of Chinese
families are able to buy desktop PCs for processing information
and accessing the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a nationwide information infrastructure is being
built with the widespread application of desktop servers and
computers in insurance, taxation, finance, commerce and power
generation.
</P>
<P>
Despite strong business challenges from IBM, Compaq, AST,
Hewlett-Packard and other international firms, Chinese companies
will continue to play a major role in the domestic PC market.
</P>
<P>
During the first four months, Chinese PC companies produced
250,000 units, up 103 percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Major PC makers such as Legend Group and Great Wall Group
turned out 102,727 units and 69,824 units, up 140 percent and 120
percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Chinese consumers owned 5 million PCs by the end of last year,
ranking second in Asia following Japan where consumers owned about
8 million units.
</P>
<P>
"But we have every reason to believe that by the year 2000, PCs
owned by Chinese families and units will surpass those owned in
Japan," Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, sales of PCs chalked up an increase of 70 percent to
2.05 million units.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
