<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Develop Wood-Based Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 10 (Xinhua) -- A Myanmar senior official has
called for setting up more forest plantations in the country to
develop wood-based industries especially by the private sector.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting here on Monday reviewing the accomplishments in
the 1996-97 fiscal year ending in March, Minister for Forestry
Chit Swe also urged modernization of the country's wood-based
industries to produce quality finished goods for the international
market, the official paper The New Light of Myanmar reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar is rich in forest resources with different types of
forests covering about 51 percent of its land area, of which 6.1
million hectares are covered with teak
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's teak export in the 1996-97 fiscal year was at 184,000
cubic meters while that of hard wood at 142,000 cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
The export of Myanmar's forest products amounted to 218 million
U.S. dollars in the 1996-97 fiscal year, accounting for 24.4
percent of the total export, second only to that of agricultural
products, according to the latest official statistics.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar restricts export of logs, banning the private sector
from exporting teak logs after the enactment of the country's
Forest Law in 1992. However, export of value-added wood-products
is encouraged.  
</P>
</TEXT>
