<HEADLINE> Thailand Upholds Death Sentence on Iranian Terrorist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 10 (Xinhua) -- A court of appeals of Thailand
Monday upheld the death sentence on an Iranian who attempted to
blow up the Israeli Embassy in Thailand in 1994 with a truck-bomb,
a local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The court upheld the ruling on the grounds that prosecutors had
substantial evidence to prosecute Iranian Hossein Shahriarifar,
The Nation said.
</P>
<P>
Shahriarifar was found guilty of murder, robbery, possession of
explosives and attempted sabotage by Bangkok South Criminal Court
in July last year, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The court also indicated that Shahriariafar's testimony that he
crossed the Thai-Malaysian border as a trader carried no weight,
as eleven witnesses identified him as the driver of the vehicle
carrying the explosives.
</P>
<P>
Shahriarifar was arrested along with two others in Hat Yai
district in southern Thailand in June 1994, ten weeks after police
found a ton of a powerful explosive mixture made from plastic
explosives and chemical fertilizer in a water tank on the back of
a six-wheel truck abandoned less than a kilometer from the Israeli
Embassy.  
</P>
