<HEADLINE> Thailand to Increase Scholarships for Africans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will increase the number
of scholarships it offers to African students to 280 a year under
a decision to be announced at an Asia-Africa conference opening
here tomorrow, according to a Thai Foreign Ministry source.
</P>
<P>
The scholarships will be offered under an existing program
which gives Africans the chance to undertake a wide range of
studies in Thailand, in fields such as agriculture, education,
health, trade, investment, tourism and environment.
</P>
<P>
The figure represents a dramatic increase from the five
scholarships offered when the program started in 1970. Last year,
100 scholarships were granted, Kobsak Chutikul, the Foreign
Ministry's director-general for economic affairs, was quoted today
by the local press as saying.
</P>
<P>
Thai Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh would announce the
plan when he opened the Second Asia-Africa Forum.
</P>
<P>
The increase would become effective next year, Kobsak said.
</P>
<P>
The three-day Asia-Africa Forum will be attended by 48 African
and 10 Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Capacity building, sustainable agricultural development and
food security and private sector development are on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
Participants are also expected to underline the importance of
political stability to economic development.  
</P>
