<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Kids in Orphanages Used in Experiment: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of children in
orphanages and babies' homes in the state of Victoria were used in
post-World War II medical experiments and research that continued
until 1970, the national newspaper the Age reported today.
</P>
<P>
The experiments included trials of new vaccines that did not
work or failed to pass safety tests in animals.
</P>
<P>
Babies less than 12 months old were injected with large doses
of an experimental vaccine against herpes. Other experiments
included giving children a test vaccine against whooping cough
which was never put into production.
</P>
<P>
An investigation by the newspaper has discovered that hundreds
of children were used to test vaccines and antigens for toxic
effects before the new products were used on children in the wider
community.
</P>
<P>
In a number of the tests babies developed adverse reactions,
including vomiting and abscesses.
</P>
<P>
Those carrying out the experiments included researchers from
the Commonwealth Serum Laboratories (CSL) and the Walter and Eliza
Hall Institute of Medical Research.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said it has identified four of the church-run or
independent institutions where experiments and tests took place.
Others remain unidentified.
</P>
<P>
In the largest experiment, which was still running in 1970, 350
infants between the ages of three months and 36 months in unnamed
institutions were injected with full adult doses of trial
influenza vaccines to test for toxic reactions.
</P>
<P>
CSL researchers admitted at the time that they approached the
test with "some trepidation" because influenza vaccines had "long
been known to produce more severe toxic reactions in children than
in adults."
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said it has learnt that two previous tests of
influenza vaccines on children produced severe toxic reactions. It
is believed that the results of the tests were never published.
</P>
<P>
Production of a whooping cough vaccine used by the CSL on
groups in babies' homes was halted after it failed to pass a
safety test in animals.
</P>
<P>
The Walter and Eliza Hall Institute of Medical Research
confirmed it had conducted tests with a killed herpes simplex
vaccine on 16 children at St. Joseph's Foundling Hospital, which
was also known as the Broadmeadows Babies' Home. The experimental
vaccine failed to protect the children against the virus.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper report did not mention how many of the orphans
were white, aboriginal or other racial backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
It said in a separate report that Victoria's crowded orphanages
and babies' homes made convenient laboratories for post-war
medical researchers.
</P>
<P>
It explained that the numbers of infants taken from their
families by the state government began rising sharply in the 1950s
because of a social policy based on the belief that children of
the poor, or those with only a single parent, would be better off
in institutions.
</P>
<P>
However, an official inquiry report issued last month said the
forced removal of tens of thousands of aboriginal children from
their homes during the 1910s-1960s constituted genocide.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
