<HEADLINE> Myanmar's Mine Production at Letpadaung to Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 10 (Xinhua) - Myanmar's annual mine production in
the Letpadaung area in the northern part of the country will reach
 63,500 tons by the year 2000, said a senior mining official.
</P>
<P>
Briefing foreign diplomats here on Monday, Myanmar Deputy
Minister for Mines U Hlaing Win said feasibility study at the
Letpadaung Hill reveals that there exist more than 400 million
tons of mineral deposits which can be exploited on a commercial
scale.
</P>
<P>
The official paper The New Light of Myanmar today quoted the
deputy minister as saying the study was conducted by Canada's
Invanhoe Company under a contract with the state-run Myanmar
Mining Enterprise.
</P>
<P>
Letpadaung is one of the areas granted to foreign companies for
mining which shows encouraging signs of becoming a major mine in
Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The two parties had earlier reached an agreement to form a
joint venture to produce 25,000 tons of copper annually from the
mineral deposits at the Kyezin and Sabei hills in Mongywa and
Salingyi townships beginning 1998, the deputy minister added.
</P>
<P>
Companies from Australia and the United States also joined in
mining other minerals such as gold, lead, zinc and nickel together
with Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest official statistics, foreign investment
in Myanmar's mining sector amounted to 498 million U.S. dollars in
42 permitted projects at the end of March this year.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's gross domestic product of mines increased by 6.5
percent in the 1996-97 fiscal year over the previous fiscal year.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
