<HEADLINE> Former Ecuadoran Minister Detained for Forging Documents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Former Ecuadoran Education and
Culture Minister Rafael Pandam was detained by police on charges
of forging travel documents for overseas travelling, police
authorities reported today.
</P>
<P>
Under the charges, Pandam changed documents for children so
that they could go abroad, particularly to the United States. He
received one thousand U.S. dollars for each service for obtaining
a U.S. visa.
</P>
<P>
The police general command office is preparing a report on this
case.
</P>
<P>
Pandam took charge of the Education and Culture Ministry under
the government of former President Abdala Bucaram who was deposed
by Congress for "mental incapacity in February of this year. The
former minister was accused of taking advantage of his official
duties and his links with local national and international
organizations to deceive diplomatic authorities for obtaining
visas for children who wish to leave the country, the authorities
said.
</P>
<P>
The police confiscated four falsified passports which
supposedly belonged to Pandam's children and an invitation to
attend an ethnological congress to be held abroad.
</P>
<P>
He appeared in the U.S. embassy several times, sparking the
suspicion of the diplomatic authorities over his formalities.
</P>
<P>
The diplomatic authorities have placed this case in the hands
of the National Police's Criminal Investigation Bureau.
</P>
<P>
In their investigations, Pandam was suspected to have
participated in sending people abroad with falsified papers.
</P>
</TEXT>
