<HEADLINE> Costa Rica Welcomes Withdrawal of Mexican Ambassador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Mexico's decision to withdraw its
new ambassador to Costa Rica after he made disparaging comments about
the government has been welcomed by politicians here.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rican Foreign Minister Fernando Naranjo said today the
presence of Mexican Ambassador Jose Rafael Castelazo, who said
Costa Rica is ruled by an oligarchy, could complicate relations
between the two countries, the media here reported.
</P>
<P>
Mexico made the right decision, because an ambassador
should not interfere in the internal affairs of another nation,
Naranjo said.
</P>
<P>
Castelazo, who only arrived in Costa Rica on May 22, was cited
by last week's edition of the Mexican magazine "Siempre", as
saying that "political power in Costa Rica is highly
concentrated. Even though there are only two principal parties,
they both belong to the same oligarchy."
</P>
<P>
He said "the government (of Costa Rica) is almost paralyzed
because it cannot make any decisions," the Siempre reported.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rican President Jose Maria Figueres refused to comment
on the Mexican government's decision, but said "our relations with
Mexico continue to be close and very good." 
</P>
</TEXT>
