<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Mark Discovery of Dunhuang Caves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, June 10 (Xinhua) -- China will hold a series of
activities in the year 2000 to mark the 100th anniversary of the
discovery of the scripture-filled caves in the Dunhuang Mogao
Grottos, located in northwest China's Gansu province.
</P>
<P>
Discovered in 1900, the grottos have five scripture-filled
caves, which once stored tens of thousands of historical books and
and art works.
</P>
<P>
Duan Wenjie, president of the Dunhuang Cultural Research
Institute, said his institute is preparing to host a large-scale
international symposium on Dunhuang studies and an exhibition of
the findigs of the caves.
</P>
<P>
The symposium will be held in 1999 in the cities of Dunhuang
and Lanzhou, the provincial capital of Gansu. Several Chinese and
overseas scholars of Dunhuang studies will be invited.
</P>
<P>
Duan said his institute also plans to collect the Dunhuang
findings on loan from various sources worldwide for an exhibition
in Dunhuang, in an effort to promote the study of Dunhuang's
history.
</P>
<P>
He said his institute promises to return the borrowed
historical relics to whoever they belong to.
</P>
<P>
Most of the scripture and artifacts found in the caves were
stolen and smuggled out of China by Western invaders long time
ago. So far, at least 13 other countries have Dunhuang cultural
relics in their possession.
</P>
<P>
The Mogao Grottos, which were carved in the face of a cliff,
dates back to 366 A.D.. Four hundred and ninety-two grottos carved
between the sixth and 14th centuries remain intact.
</P>
<P>
The Dunhuang Mogao Grottos, designated as one of the world's
treasure-houses of cultural relics by the United Nations
Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO), are
known for their murals and the extensive collection of
literature. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0247 </DOCNO>
