<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chongqing Pledges to Help Raise Up Its Poor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Chongqing, a newly-established
municipality directly under the State Council, is determined to do
all it can to eliminate poverty in the next two years, China Daily
reported today.
</P>
<P>
To help do so, the municipality is on the watch for new
investors.
</P>
<P>
"It will not be easy for Chongqing to lift its 3.6 million poor
rural residents, mostly in Wanxian and Fuling counties, out of
poverty before the end of the century," Zhou Jianzhong, vice-mayor
of Chongqing, said.
</P>
<P>
But Zhou was confident that the municipality would try its best
to realize that goal by accelerating the development of local
infrastructures and making full use of its resources.
</P>
<P>
The major difference between Chongqing, which has 30 million
inhabitants, and China's three other giant cities -- Beijing,
Shanghai and Tianjin each with a population of more than 10
million -- is the proportion of the poor in Chongqing: one-10th of
its population falls below the State-set poverty line.
</P>
<P>
The State's annual funding earmarked for the municipality's
help-the-poor program has reached 450 million yuan (54 million US
dollars), Zhou said.
</P>
<P>
Such an amount of funds earmarked for the megacity's
help-the-poor program has been much more than other provinces,
but more investments are necessary.
</P>
<P>
Zhou made it clear that the top priority for building up a new
Chongqing is the development of transportation, energy and
communication infrastructures in order to improve the local
investment environment.
</P>
<P>
The vice-mayor is urging overseas investors to introduce
advanced technology and funding to take a hand in the construction
of a new Chongqing, freeing all its inhabitants from the yoke of
poverty.
</P>
<P>
Promising opportunities abound for overseas investors,
particularly in the construction of highways and in side-line
production processing with already available local resources, Zhou
said.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing used to be part of Sichuan province, the country's
largest pork-producing and processing center. The municipality
raises 1.8 million pigs a year but only 1.3 million -- 70 percent,
are sold annually.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhou, construction of several highways, including
the section from Chengdu to Fuling and the highway from Shanghai
to Chengdu, will begin this year. They will improve the city's
transportation network and are obvious projects for overseas
investors.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Chongqing encompasses many arable fields suitable for
use as orchards, particularly for oranges and tangerines. The city
is located next to China's largest orange and tangerine orchards
along the Yangtze River. Investors interested in developing a
fruit-processing industry, especially soft-drinks, would have on
hand rich local resources.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing is now negotiating with a company from the United
States for a project in Wanxian to produce fresh fruit juice.
</P>
<P>
The municipality also is about to introduce advanced
cultivation techniques from Israel for growing vegetables.
</P>
<P>
In the last few years, Chongqing has succeeded in developing
its orchards and fishponds by using loans granted by the World
Bank. With the help of European Economic Community donations, the
city has begun producing milk products, Zhou said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0249 </DOCNO>
