<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia To Step up Military Ties With Vietnam, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Australia plans to step up its
military ties with Vietnam and the Philippines with agreements
soon to be announced with the two countries to regularly share
sensitive information on defense and strategic issues.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper the Australian said today that just 22 years
after the end of the Vietnam War, the federal government of
Australia will unveil plans for the first official
political-military talks with Hanoi's regime within the next few
weeks.
</P>
<P>
The historic agreement with Vietnam -- reached in senior
Foreign Ministry officials' talks in Canberra on May 30 -- comes

as Australia plans to announce an agreement on similar security
exchanges with the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The first round of talks with the two countries is expected to
be held before the end of the year and attended by defense and
diplomatic security specialists, including Vice Admiral Chris
Barrie, vice chief of the Australian Defense Force.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam and the Philippines are vital elements of a strategy to
be confirmed in the forthcoming foreign policy White Paper to
create a web of security arrangements which embraces every leading
East Asian military power.
</P>
<P>
In the past two years, Australia has reached agreement for
so-called "polmil" talks with Japan and the Republic of Korea,
signed a security treaty with Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Following the agreements with Vietnam and the Philippines,
Australian officials are aiming to conclude negotiations for
security talks with Thailand by the end of the year, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
It is likely to be joined later by India. Senior defense
officials are due to go to New Delhi by the end of the year to
discuss options for establishing regular defense exchanges.
</P>
<P>
The push to expand security ties started with the previous
government but has gathered pace in the past year. Behind the move
is a deliberate strategy aimed at avoiding the outbreak of
conflict through the greater sharing of defense and strategic
information and other confidence building measures.
</P>
<P>
Australia's foreign policy White Paper, due to be released
mid-year by Foreign Minister Alexander Downer, emphasizes this
approach by restating the need to seek "security in and with the
region" by building bilateral defense and security relationships.
</P>
<P>
Australia's navy has 12 ship visits planned to ports in the
Philippines this year at a time when U.S. naval ship visits have
been suspended because of a dispute between Manila and Washington
over an armed forces agreement.
</P>
<P>
Australia is now the biggest defense partner of the Philippine
armed forces, offering extensive training under a 3.2 million U.S.
dollar defense aid program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
