<HEADLINE> German's Hoechst Signs a Joint Venture Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Hoechst Group, one of the top
three chemical companies in Germany, has signed a 29 million US
dollar joint venture with a company in east China's Jiangsu
province to produce food preservatives, today's China Daily
reported.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture with Hoechst holding 60 percent of the equity
and its partner, the Nanjing Chemical Industrial Group Co., taking
the other 40 percent, will be capable of producing 4,000 tons of
sorbic acid and potassium sorbate a year. This will enable them to
capture a bigger share of Asia's food ingredient market, the
English-language newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Sorbic acid and potassium sorbate have proved to be highly
efficient and safe preservatives with a broad range of application
for food and beverage products.
</P>
<P>
The Nanning group is the largest chemical enterprise in
southern China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region. Hoechst, with
its focus on health care, agronutrition and industry, reported
32.6 billion US dollars in total sales last year. 
</P>
