<HEADLINE> Italian, South African Ministers Talk on Bilateral Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini
held talks here today with South African Trade and Industry
Minister Alec Erwin on ways to expand bilateral trade ties.
</P>
<P>
Trade between the two countries has grown steadily over the
last few years. Italy has moved up from being South Africa's
seventh largest trading partner to fifth. In 1995, Italian exports
to South Africa rose 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
But the two men agreed that the countries should further tap
the great potential for cooperation, between enterprises and trade
and financial sectors.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers signed an agreement on the promotion and
protection of investments as a follow up to a double taxation
agreement concluded at the end of 1995.
</P>
<P>
They also discussed South Africa's negotiations for a free
trade agreement with the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Erwin, who arrived in Rome today, will open an investment
conference Tuesday in Milan which is expected to be attended by a
large number of Italian businessmen and entrepreneurs from both
public and private sectors.
</P>
<P>
A similar conference to present Italy to the South African
business community was held in South Africa last year. 
