<HEADLINE> Sino-Italian Aluminium Plant to Set An Example </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- A major Sino-Italian co-operative
project, the Chengdu Aluminium Foil Plant was inaugurated by
Italy's Foreign Trade Minister Augusto Fantozzi yesterday in
Chengdu, capital of southwest China's Sichuan province.
</P>
<P>
It is to serve as an example for prospective Italian businesses
in the country, said today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Four aluminium plate and foil rolling lines, from Turin-based
Fata Hunter, a leading aluminium industry developer and
contractor, were announced to be in full operation at the plant, a
700 million yuan (84 million US dollars) investment.
</P>
<P>
With the 31 million US dollars worth of Italian-built
equipment, the plant is to produce high-grade aluminium plates and
foils for flexible packaging of products for the growing food and
pharmaceutical industries.
</P>
<P>
Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi, leading a 130-member
business delegation, visited China last week. The delegation
remains in the country and Fantozzi, who leads the delegation now,
said a new era in cooperation with China is expected.
</P>
<P>
Fata Hunter, a key division of the diversified Fata industrial
group, also has provided the Chinese plant with technical
assistance and personnel training.
</P>
<P>
Fata Hunter was awarded the contract for the four rolling lines
for the plant in 1992 by the China National Technical Import and
Export Corp (CNTIC) in an international tender that elicited
competition from British, French and German companies.
</P>
<P>
Fata Managing Director Ignazio Moncada, a member of the Italian
delegation, said that the successful operation of the project had
proven CNTIC's decision wise.
</P>
<P>
The plant received financial support from the government of
Kuwait through the Kuwait Fund and the Italian SACE-Medicocredito
through export credits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
