<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hebei Revives State Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Hebei province is renewing its
campaign to invigorate its 14,000 State-owned enterprises,
according to China Daily today.
</P>
<P>
A major step to stimulate the drive, according to Deputy
Governor Guo Shichang, is to get more firms to follow the
successful example of the State-owned Handan Iron and Steel Group
Co Ltd, which not only has survived fierce market competition, but
is thriving.
</P>
<P>
Some 6,723 State-owned enterprises are now involved in the
campaign, Guo said, of which 3,892 have improved their management
procedures since the drive started in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Enlightened by the example of the Handan Group, 1,345
enterprises have adapted to compete in a market economy and now
offer workers incentives for better performance.
</P>
<P>
The Handan Group was a money-losing business in the days of
central economic planning. When the State began pressing its
enterprises to become market-oriented, Handan took appropriate
measures to meet the requirements of surviving in a market economy.
</P>
<P>
Under a centralized plan, prices were determined by what it
cost to manufacture goods. The price was far higher than the
market was willing to pay.
</P>
<P>
Shoved into the fierce market economy, where it was sink or
swim, Handan priced its products in line with what customers were
willing to pay. Meanwhile, Handan cut production and management
costs by eliminating waster and inefficient managerial practices.
</P>
<P>
Handan stood out like a beacon amid many other iron and steel
producers which had failed to adjust to the often brutal market
conditions and continued to bleed money. Handan paid off its debts
and began to make money. Last year, it reported a profit of 700
million yuan (84 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Another step to revitalize the province's State enterprises is
to encourage and support the development of large State firms,
particularly those with comparatively good performance records,
Guo said.
</P>
<P>
The province will support and encourage the development of 100
such companies, Guo said.
</P>
<P>
Hebei intends to create 30 pillar industry groups by the year
2000, the deputy governor said.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government is expected to offer a set of
preferential policies to enterprises that upgrade their
technologies, develop their funding sources and move into the
export-import trade.
</P>
<P>
Hebei will not neglect its smaller firms, Guo said. The
province has 10,780 small State firms employing 700,000
workers. Their assets come to 29.1 billion yuan (3.5 million US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Although these firms do not play a vital role in Hebei's
economy, they contribute to it by providing re-employment
opportunities to local workers and revenue to the county-level
governments.
</P>
<P>
To salvage the money-losing small businesses, Guo said, many
have merged, or become limited corporations or share-holding
companies with interests spread among several enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
