<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vast Forest Area Springs Up in Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- More than 2.2 million hectares of
bare land in China was converted into forest during the spring,
said today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
More than half the year's tree planting plan had been
accomplished by the end of April, according to the Ministry of
Forestry.
</P>
<P>
In fact, it has almost certainly exceeded that quota, said Chen
Yingfa, a ministry official.
</P>
<P>
This year is regarded as critical to achieve the country's
afforestation target of raising China's forest coverage to 15.5
percent by the year 2000, compared with the present 13.92 percent.
</P>
<P>
In general, spring forest conversion accounts for a large
percentage of the total in a year in China.
</P>
<P>
Most of the trees this spring were planted by a land-based
workforce. But China also deploys airplanes which encircle
mountains to plant and nurture trees in high and remote areas that
are difficult to reach.
</P>
<P>
Many volunteers in major cities took part in the spring tree
planting campaign, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
Deng Xiaoping, the late senior Chinese leader who died in
February, had been a primary advocate of the tree planting drive.
</P>
<P>
More than 4.5 million people in Beijing volunteered to plant
trees this spring. And about 100 million trees were planted by
volunteers in Chongqing, doubling the city's target for the whole
year.
</P>
<P>
More and more farmers would like to plant trees on their land
rather than cultivate less-lucrative crops, Chen said. This is in
line with the forestry-coverage policies in provinces such as
Shaanxi with its barren Loess Plateau.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen is one of the cities which has increased its
investment to promote afforestation.
</P>
<P>
It invested more than 100 million yuan (12 million US dollars)
this year to plant trees, half of which will be used to green
roads.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
