<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Urged to End Its Occupation of Palestine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 9 (Xinhua) -- A UN committee said today
that the international committee must recommit itself to ending
the decade-long illegal occupation by Israel of the Palestinian
territory, including Jerusalem and other Arab territories.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting to mark the 30th anniversary of the Israeli
occupation, the Committee on the Exercise of the Inalienable
Rights of the Palestinian People said that as a direct result of
the Israeli occupation, the Palestinian people were living at
hostages in their own land and had not been able to enjoy their
inalienable rights under the UN Charter and the Universal
Declaration of Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
In a statement delivered at the meeting, Ibra Deguene Ka of
Senegal, chairman of the Palestinian Rights Committee, said that
the Middle East peace process remained laborious, intense and
difficult. The Palestinian people were surrounded by the thicket
of Jewish settlements in the West Bank, including Jerusalem and
the Gaza Strip. Declared Israeli plans for new settlements
jeopardized the livelihood of present and future generations of
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"Thirty years of occupation had a devastating impact on the
economic activity of the West Bank and the Gaza Strip," he said.
</P>
<P>
Russian ambassador Sergey Lavrov, president of the Security
Council for June, said that as the Palestinian people were going
through a crucial transition phase, fraught with set-backs, it was
of paramount importance that the international community continued
to work hard to make the peace process a genuine success.
</P>
<P>
Felipe Mabilangan, vice-president of the General Assembly,
reading out a statement by Assembly President Razali Ismail, said
the question of Palestine remained the most intractable conflict
situation in the history of the United Nations. It was regrettable
that the prospect of a just and durable peace for the peoples of
Palestine and the Middle East was now seriously at risk and had
been jeopardized owing to recent actions taken by the Israeli
Government, he said.
</P>
<P>
Julio Londono-Paredes of Colombia, reading a statement by the
President of Colombia in his capacity as chairman of the Movement
of Non-Aligned Countries, said that the decision to proceed with
the settlements at Jabal Abu Ghneim, in flagrant violation of the
Madrid and Oslo agreements, had altered the atmosphere of
cordiality and frankness in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
At this delicate juncture, the Non-Aligned Movement reiterated
its unflinching support for the legitimate struggle of the
Palestinian people for self-determination and independence, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Arizal Effendi of Indonesia, speaking on behalf of his foreign
minister in his capacity as chairman of the 24th Islamic
Conference of Foreign Ministers, urged Israel to fully and
consistently comply with the provisions of its agreements with the
Palestinians and proceed with final status negotiations, based on
recognition of the inalienable rights of the Palestinians as an
independent state.
</P>
<P>
Machivenyika Tobia Mapuranga of Zimbabwe, reading a message
from the president of Zimbabwe in his capacity as chairman of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU), stated that the OAU had kept
the situation in the Middle East, and especially Palestine, as
permanent items on its agenda and had consistently opposed any
attempts to derail the peace process. The OAU considered all
measures and actions taken by Israel to change the legal status of
Jerusalem as null and void, as they violated the letter and spirit
of the Declaration of Principles, he said.
</P>
<P>
UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan and observers for Palestine and
for the League of Arab States also made statements at today's
meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Finnish Kankunnen Leads Acropolis Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Juha Kankunnen of Finland, who is
driving a Ford escort, continued to lead the 44th Acropolis rally
after completing the first three special sections of Monday's
second leg.
</P>
<P>
However, another Finnish driver, Tommi Makinen, dropped to
fourth after being equal second with Britain's Richard Burns at
the end of the first day Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Burns is in second place, just ahead of Spain's Carlos Sainz.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Colin Mcrae, kankunnen's main championship rival, had
led the rally after the first stage Sunday but he hit a bank on
the second and was forced out of the race.
</P>
<P>
Kenneth Eriksson of Sweden was forced to abandan the Acropolis
rally after his car developed engine problems in the first special
section of the second leg Monday.
</P>
<P>
The rally covers a total distance of 1,263 kilometers, which
includes 20 special sections stretching 458 kilometers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
