<HEADLINE> Rubin Says US Supports Strong Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 9 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert
Rubin said today that the U.S. government still supports a strong
dollar despite the U.S. currency reaching a six-month low against
the Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
"We favor a strong dollar as we always have, and for the
reasons we always have -- it helps keep inflation down, it helps
keep interest rates down, both of which are good for the economy,"
Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
Rubin made the remark when he was questioned at a White House
briefing today on congressional budget negotiations as the dollar
fell again in early New York trading to 1.7143 German marks and
112.63 Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. dollar fell to an intraday low of 111.80 yen, the
weakest since December 6 of last year, before partly recovering to
settle at 112.93 yen in New York today, down from 114.60 yen last
Friday. 
</P>
