<HEADLINE> UN Continues to Reduce Peacekeeping Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations will
reduce its budget for peacekeeping operations by nearly 30 percent
for the period from 1 July 1997 to 30 June 1998 over the previous
12 months, according to the Fifth Committee (Administrative and
Budgetary).
</P>
<P>
At a meeting today, the the Fifth Committee approved the
peacekeeping budgets amounting to 853 million dollars for the
12-month period starting from next month, compared to the 1.2
billion dollars for the period from 1 July 1996 to 30 June 1997.
</P>
<P>
The budgets, which should be adopted by the General Assembly,
cover financing of UN missions on borders between Israel and
Syria, between Iraq and Kuwait, and peacekeeping forces in
Lebanon, Cyprus, Georgia and eight other countries.
</P>
<P>
Appropriations were also approved for the UN Peace Forces in
the former Yugoslavia, the UN Mission in Haiti and the UN
Assistance Mission for Rwanda, closed missions in the process of
liquidation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
