<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Host 1999 Universal Postal Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERN, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The People's Republic of China will
host the last Universal Postal Congress in the 20th century,
according to an official agreement signed here today between China
and the Universal Postal Union (UPU).
</P>
<P>
The next Universal Postal Congress will be held in Beijing from
August 23 to September 15, 1999. China's Minister of Posts and
Telecommunications Wu Jichuan and Director General of the
International Bureau of the UPU Thomas Leavey signed the agreement
at the UPU's headquarters in the Swiss capital of Bern.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the signing ceremony, Wu Jichuan said that the
Chinese government attaches great importance to the development of
the post and is there therefore giving special attention to the
upcoming Universal Postal Congress.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin is the honorary chairman of the
Chinese Organizing Committee for the Congress established on July
18, 1996. What President Jiang has written for the Congress,
"Developing the modern post to meet social needs," has expressed
his expectations for the progress of the post in China and other
parts of the world, Wu said.
</P>
<P>
Leavey stressed that China will take up an important leadership
role after the congress as the chairman of the UPU's newly elected
Council of Administration. The host country will further benefit
by the large number of foreign visitors attending the Congress
while Chinese and other stamps will be on show at the philatelic
exhibition to be held during the congress, Leavey said.
</P>
<P>
He said the UPU congress should further result in development
opportunities for staff members of the Chinese Department of Posts
and Telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
About 2,000 delegates from 189 postal administrations of the
UPU's member countries, restricted postal unions and various
governmental and non-governmental organizations are expected to
attend one of the biggest international gatherings on the Chinese
calendar for 1999.
</P>
<P>
Leavey said the Beijing congress is of special significance as
it will take place at the dawn of the next millennium and will
serve as a platform for postal services to discuss ways and means
to ensure that the postal service keeps track with the latest
technological developments in a highly competitive communications
environment and adapts to the new realities of a rapidly changing
economic world.
</P>
<P>
As one of the United Nations agencies, the UPU was founded in
1874. The Universal Postal Congress, held once every five years,
is the highest governing body of the UPU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
