<HEADLINE> Religious Leaders Issue Joint Call for Peace in Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of Bosnia's four religions
today jointly called on the leadership and people of the country
to pursue "a durable peace based on truth, justice and common
living."
</P>
<P>
The joint statement was signed by Dr Mustafa Ceric, chief of
the Islamic Community, chief priest Metropolit Nikolaj of Orthodox
Church, Cardinal Pulijic of Roman Catholic and Jakob Finci,
president of the Jeswish Community.
</P>
<P>
The religious leaders said in the statement that they were
concerned by the "visibly slow and inefficient implementation of
the civilian provisions of Dayton peace accords and deeply
disturbed by "recent unpleasant events in the Zone of Separation,"
referring to demolition of abandoned houses and clashs between
Muslim refugees and Serb police in the inter-entity boundary
areas.
</P>
<P>
"The peoples of Bosnia-Herzegovina have undergone enormous
suffering," said the statement. "Our task now is to establish a
durable peace based on truth, justice and common living."
</P>
<P>
The leaders condemned specially the acts of hatred, the
obstruction of free right to return, the acts of revenge and the
abuse of the media with the aim of spreading hatred. They also
expressed their concern at the burning of houses, the desecration
of religious buildings and the destruction of graveyards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
