<HEADLINE> US Dollar Falls Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar hit a six-month
low against the yen and ended sharply weaker in other dealings
today.
</P>
<P>
Investors were worrying about Japan's trade surplus and feared
that France will delay the euro, which helped the mark.
</P>
<P>
The possibility that Europe's single currency won't be launched
as scheduled in January 1999, attracted the attention of many
traders throughout the session.
</P>
<P>
The dollar fell to an intraday low of 111.80 yen, the weakest
since last December 6, before partly recovering to settle at
112.93 yen in New York, down from 114.60 Friday. Since reaching a
three-year high of 127.47 yen on May 1, the dollar has fallen
about 11 percent against the Japanese currency.
</P>
<P>
Against the mark, the dollar fell to an intraday low of 1.7049
marks, the weakest this month, before settling in New York at
1.7072 marks, down from 1.7258 Friday. The pound cost 1.6367 U.S.
dollars, up from 1.6316 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Other late-dollar rates in New York compared with late Friday:
1.4388 Swiss francs, down from 1.4517; 5.7675 French francs, down
from 5.8280; 1,687.50 Italian lire, down from 1,699.25; 1.3875
Canadian dollars, up from 1.3831. 
</P>
