<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Says NATO Membership Not Free </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The United States today said
that a membership of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO)
is not a "free lunch" and new members would have to pay.
</P>
<P>
"Joining NATO is not free. This is about security," said Robert
Hunter, U.S. ambassador to NATO. "It's about mutual pledges of one
country to another."
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference here that any country that thinks
it's going to be free should not apply for the membership.
</P>
<P>
NATO leaders would choose the first group of countries as new
members at their special summit meeting in Madrid in July. Poland,
Hungary and the Czech Republic are on top of the list.
</P>
<P>
Estimates on the cost range from eight to 10 billion U.S.
dollars during the next 10 years covering the first wave of
expansion.
</P>
<P>
Hunter said that there are three levels of the cost, including
"what new countries do for themselves," NATO itself and assistance
to new members by individual NATO countries.
</P>
<P>
"Now all of the NATO allies will accept their full fair share
of this NATO budget, because we have worked this out many years in
the past. We pay -- the United States -- about 26 percent on
average," he added.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. estimates that it will have to invest between 150
million U.S. dollars and 200 million U.S. dollars a year in NATO's
expansion in the next 12 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970610.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US, Peru Agree to Protect Artifacts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. and Peru today signed
an agreement to restrict importing certain pre-Columbian
archaeological and ethnic materials into the United States from
Peru without an export permit.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Assistant Secretary of State for Inter-American Affairs
Jeffrey Davidow and Peruvian Ambassador Ricardo Luna signed the
pact at the Peruvian embassy in Washington.
</P>
<P>
The accord is aimed at stemming the unauthorized transport of
cultural objects across borders.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, royal tombs at Sipan, Peru, will continue
to be protected as will the archaeological remains of the cultural
groups that developed in Peru from approximately 12,000 B.C. to
A.D. 1532.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year the United states signed similar accords with
Canada and El Salvador. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
