<HEADLINE> Ralston Drops Bid for US Joint Chiefs Chairman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 9 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Air Force General Joseph
Ralston today withdrew his name from consideration as the chairman
of the Joint Chiefs of Staff because of an adulterous affair a
decade ago.
</P>
<P>
Ralston said in a statement that he made the decision "with a
sense of regret."
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary William Cohen, in a statement issued at the
Pentagon, said Ralston would remain as vice chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
"General Ralston believes that a prolonged fight for Senate
confirmation would be harmful to his family and would be a
distraction from other serious national security issues," Cohen
said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
Ralston was considered the top candidate for the seat until he
admitted to having had an adulterous affair 13 years ago and
that brought criticism from lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
Several high-ranking officers have retired or been relieved
recently after admitting to improper sexual conduct.
</P>
<P>
Seeing the lawmakers were not supportive, Ralston informed
Cohen of his intentions this afternoon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
