<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Computer Software Giant to Acquire Cable TV Stake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 9 (Xinhua) -- The Microsoft Corporation, the
largest software designer in the United States, is nearing a deal
to invest 1 billion U.S. dollars in the Comcast Corporation, the
nation's sixth-largest cable television operator, the New York
Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The move, which was said to be the most aggressive beyond the
software arena and into the media business, would give the
computer software giant a crucial foothold in controlling and
distributing television programming, the report said.
</P>
<P>
In one deal after another over the last two years, the
Microsoft Corporation has shown its determination to have a big
role in creating and distributing information and entertainment
over whatever technologies exist or may emerge.
</P>
<P>
In the current deal, the company's immediate interest is in
using Comcast's distribution pipeline for the Microsoft Network,
an information service that the company has created to compete
with on-line services.
</P>
<P>
If completed, the deal would match up the nation's largest
software designer with one of the cable industry's most
independent family-owned companies. Comcast, which is based in
Philadelphia in the eastern United States, has built a 4 billion
U.S. dollar company with properties in cable, television, cellular
telephone and home shopping. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
